RL   Genetica 107(1-3), 27-37 (1999).
XX
DR   GenBank; AC005936; Positions   19502    3688.
XX
CC   ARNOLD1 is an autonomous DNA transposon. It is bordered by a
CC   perfect
CC   9 bp-long target site duplication. This DNA transposon does not
CC   have
CC   terminal inverted repeats. It encodes MUDRA-like transposase and
CC   one/two additional proteins in direct and reverse orientations,
CC   respectively. The additional protein includes a transmembrane
CC   domain related to the one present in proteins from the drug
CC   resistance
CC   translocase family (also known as the major facilitator family).
CC   This structural feature links ARNOLD1 transposon with bacterial
CC   transposons many of which are well known to be carriers of drug
CC   resistance genes.
CC   ARNOLD-like autonomous transposons are/were responsible,
CC   putatively,
CC   for a proliferation of ARNOLDY-like non-autonomous DNA
CC   transposons
CC   and mini- and micro-satellites.
XX

RT   thaliana.";
RL   Genetica 107(1-3), 27-37 (1999).

DR   GenBank; AC006298; Positions   73335   88824.
XX
CC   ARNOLD2 is an autonomous DNA transposon. It is bordered by a
CC   perfect
CC   9 bp-long target site duplication. This DNA transposon does not
CC   have
CC   terminal inverted repeats. It encodes MUDRA-like transposase and
CC   one/two additional proteins in direct and reverse orientations,
CC   respectively. The additional protein includes a transmembrane
CC   domain related to the one present in proteins from the drug
CC   resistance
CC   translocase family (also known as the major facilitator family).
CC   This structural feature links ARNOLD2 transposon with bacterial
CC   transposons many of which are well known to be carriers of drug
CC   resistance genes.
CC   ARNOLD-like autonomous transposons are/were responsible,
CC   putatively,
CC   for a proliferation of ARNOLDY-like non-autonomous DNA
CC   transposons.
XX
SQ   Sequence 15490 BP; 4784 A; 2901 C; 2187 G; 5614 T; 4 other;

RT   "ARNOLD3.";

RN   [2]
RA   Kapitonov V.V. and Jurka J.;
RT   "Molecular paleontology of transposable elements from Arabidopsis
RT   thaliana.";
RL   Genetica 107(1-3), 27-37 (1999).

DR   GenBank; AF096371; Positions   23139   37862.
XX
CC   ARNOLD3 is an autonomous DNA transposon. It is bordered by a
CC   perfect
CC   9 bp-long target site duplication. This DNA transposon does not
CC   have
CC   terminal inverted repeats. It encodes MUDRA-like transposase and
CC   one/two additional proteins in direct and reverse orientations,
CC   respectively. The additional protein includes a transmembrane
CC   domain related to the one present in proteins from the drug
CC   resistance
CC   translocase family (also known as the major facilitator family).
CC   This structural feature links ARNOLD3 transposon with bacterial
CC   transposons many of which are well known to be carriers of drug
CC   resistance genes.
CC   ARNOLD-like autonomous transposons are/were responsible,
CC   putatively,
CC   for a proliferation of ARNOLDY-like non-autonomous DNA
CC   transposons.
XX
SQ   Sequence 14724 BP; 4598 A; 2699 C; 2139 G; 5288 T; 0 other;

CC   ARNOLD4 is an autonomous DNA transposon. It is bordered by a
CC   perfect
CC   9 bp-long target site duplication. This DNA transposon does not
CC   have
CC   terminal inverted repeats. It encodes MUDRA-like transposase and
CC   one/two additional proteins in direct and reverse orientations,
CC   respectively. The additional protein includes a transmembrane
CC   domain related to the one present in proteins from the drug
CC   resistance
CC   translocase family (also known as the major facilitator family).
CC   This structural feature links ARNOLD4 transposon with bacterial
CC   transposons many of which are well known to be carriers of drug
CC   resistance genes.
CC   ARNOLD-like autonomous transposons are/were responsible,
CC   putatively,
CC   for a proliferation of ARNOLDY-like non-autonomous DNA
CC   transposons.
XX

DR   [1] (Consensus)
XX
CC   ARNOLDY1 is a consensus sequence of non-autonomous DNA
CC   transposons
CC   from ARNOLDY1 family. Individual copies are bordered by 9 bp-long
CC   target site duplications. ARNOLDY1 shares terminal regions with
CC   ARNOLDs autonomous DNA transposons. Presumably, ARNOLDs are/were
CC   responsible for a proliferation of ARNOLDYs in the A.thaliana.

CC   AT9MU1 is an autonomous DNA transposon involved in transposition
CC   of AT9NMU1 nonautonomous elements. Transposase is encoded by two
CC   putative exons (857-1427 and 1505-1648); it may be a N-truncated
CC   form of a complete protein. There is a putative protein of
CC   unknown function encoded by the second strand.

DR   [1] (Consensus)
XX
CC   AT9NMU1 is a nonautonomous DNA transposon.
CC   There are 20-100 copies of the transposon in the A.thaliana
CC   genome which are 98% identical to the consensus sequence.
CC   It has 150-bp identical TIRs and is flanked by 9-bp duplications
CC   of target sites.
CC   Putatively, its autonomous-like relative is deposited in Repbase
CC   as AT9MU1 transposon.
XX

RT   "AT9TSD1.";
RL   Direct Submission to Repbase Update (JAN-2001).
XX
DR   [1] (Consensus)
XX
CC   AT9TSD1 is a nonautonomous DNA transposon.
CC   There are at least 5 copies of AT9TSD1 in the genome;
CC   they are ~97% identical with the consensus sequence.
CC   AT9TSD1 has 12-bp terminal inverted repeats;
CC   Since AT9TSD1 copies are flanked by 9-bp target site
CC   duplications,
CC   it's very likely that MuDR-like transposase was a catalyst of
CC   AT9TSD1 transpositions in a recent past. Its 5'-GGA...TCC-3'
CC   termini
CC   hint also a relation with MuDR-like transposons.
XX

RN   [2]
RA   Kapitonov V.V. and Jurka J.;
RT   "Molecular paleontology of transposable elements from Arabidopsis
RT   thaliana.";
RL   Genetica 107(1-3), 27-37 (1999).
XX
DR   [1] (Consensus)
XX
CC   ATCOPIA10_I is a consensus sequence of internal region of a
CC   recently
CC   active ATCOPIA10 Copia-like retroelement. The consensus sequence
CC   has
CC   been reconstructed based on two provirus sequences found on
CC   chromosomes 4 and 5. Internal sequences of these proviruses are
CC   94% identical to each other and they are flanked by 5 bp-long
CC   target-site duplications. Interestingly, there is only 85%
CC   identity
CC   between LTRs flanking different proviruses although every
CC   provirus
CC   is flanked by 97% identical LTRs.
CC   ATCOPIA10_I ORF (position 53-4138) codes for 1361 aa-long
CC   Copia-like polyprotein.
CC   The name has been changed from ATSASHA4I to ATCOPIA10_I (Dec.16,
CC   1999).
XX

CC   ATCOPIA18A_I is an internal region of the ATCOPIA18A Copia-like
CC   endogenous retrovirus flanked by the 99% identical ATCOPIA18ALTR
CC   long terminal repeats, and a 5-bp target-site duplication
CC   (GTGTT).
CC   ATCOPIA18A is a subfamily of the ATCOPIA18 family.
CC   There is a 77% identity between the ATCOPIA18A_I and ATCOPIA18I
CC   internal sequences.
CC   ATCOPIA18A_I encodes remnants of the ATCOPIA18Ap Copia-like
CC   polyprotein. The ORF which encodes ATCOPIA18Ap is slightly
CC   damaged
CC   by false stop codons and other mutations.
XX

CC   ATCOPIA26 is a recently active Copia-like LTR retrotransposon,
CC   it has 5 bp-long target-site duplication, and its LTRs,
CC   ATCOPIA26LTR, are 99% identical. Its internal region, ATCOPIA26I,
CC   encodes 1489-aa Copia-like polyprotein (position 138-4595).

CC   Copia-like retroelement flanked by identical ATCOPIA31_LTR

CC   active

CC   duplications

CC   sequence, and the second half is present in the AC006250

CC   ATCOPIA38A_I is an internal region of the ATCOPIA38A Copia-like
CC   endogenous retrovirus flanked by 2% divergent ATCOPIA38ALTR
CC   long terminal repeats and a 5-bp target-site duplication
CC   (ATTCA). CDS is slightly damaged.
CC   ATCOPIA38A_I is ~20% divergent from ATCOPIA38_I and ATCOPIA38B_I.

CC   ATCOPIA38B_I is an internal portion of ATCOPIA38B, a recently
CC   active
CC   Copia-like LTR retrotransposon; it is flanked by 5-bp
CC   duplications
CC   of a target site. Its long terminal repeats, deposited in Repbase
CC   Update as ATCOPIA38B_LTR, are 99% identical to each other.
CC   There are 80% nucleotide identity between ATCOPIA38_I and
CC   ATCOPIA38B_I, and 68% nucleotide identity between ATCOPIA38_LTR
CC   and ATCOPIA38B_LTR.

CC   ATCOPIA42I is an internal region of the ATCOPIA42 Copia-like
CC   endogenous retrovirus flanked by ATCOPIA42LTR; 5-bp target-site
CC   duplication. The consensus sequence was derived from three
CC   copies,
CC   they are ~95% identical to the consensus sequence.
CC   Gag and RT portions of a Copia-like polyprotein encoded by
CC   ATCOPIA42I
CC   are damaged by several false stop-codons.

DR   [2] (Consensus)
XX
CC   ATCOPIA43I is a consensus sequence of an internal portion
CC   of ATCOPIA43 Copia-like endogenous retrovirus. Its long
CC   terminal repeat is deposited as ATCOPIA43LTR. The consensus
CC   sequence was derived from five copies (they represent two
CC   subfamilies) ATCOPIA43I copies are ~98% identical to the
CC   consensus sequence.
CC   This retrovirus is closer to SIRE1 from Glycine max than to
CC   other Copia-like endogenous retroviruses present in the
CC   A.thaliana genome. ATCOPIA43I encodes the 1659aa gag-pol
CC   polyprotein (position 144-5123) and the 475aa
CC   envelope-like protein (position 6074-7501).
XX

DR   [1] (Consensus)
XX
CC   ATCOPIA43LTR is a consensus sequence of a long terminal repeat
CC   from ATCOPIA43 Copia-like endogenous retrovirus.
CC   Individual copies are ~97% identical to the consensus sequence.
CC   There are ~10 copies of the ATCOPIA43LTR in the genome.
CC   Solo LTRs are flanked by 5-bp target site duplications.
XX

CC   ATCOPIA48_I is an internal region of the ATCOPIA48 Copia-like
CC   endogenous retrovirus flanked by the 98% identical ATCOPIA48LTR
CC   long terminal repeats, and by the 5-bp target-site duplication
CC   (GAAGT). ATCOPIA48_I CDS, which encodes the ATCOPIA48p Copia-like
CC   polyprotein, is interrupted by a non-LTR retrotransposon inserted
CC   recently in the genome. Presumably, the insertion has induced a
CC   2629-bp duplication which flanks the insert. Both the non-LTR
CC   retrotransposon and a copy of the 2629-bp direct repeat were
CC   removed from the ATCOPIA48_I sequence reported here.
XX

CC   ATCOPIA49 Copia-like endogenous retrovirus; there are 3 copies of
CC   ATCOPIA49_I present in the genome, they are flanked by ~2%
CC   divergent ATCOPIA47LTR, and by 5 bp-long target-site
CC   duplications.
CC   These copies are 1% divergent from the consensus sequence.
CC   ATCOPIA49_I encodes the 1361-aa ATCOPIA49p Copia-like
CC   polyprotein.

CC   ATCOPIA4I is an internal region of a Copia-like
CC   LTR-retrotransposon
CC   ATCOPIA4. ATCOPIA4 can be a currently active element since its
CC   LTRs,
CC   ATCOPIA4LTR, are identical. ATCOPIA4 has 5 bp-long target site
CC   duplication. Its left and right LTRs have been wrongly identified
CC   by
CC   the authors deposited Z02342 locus in GenBank as two solo LTRs.
CC   Also, the Copia-like polyprotein encoded by ATCOPIA4I was wrongly
CC   annotated as a part of 2000 aa-long protein (see GenBank,
CC   Z97342).
XX

CC   ATCOPIA54_I is an internal region of the ATCOPIA54 Copia-like
CC   endogenous retrovirus flanked by the 7% divergent ATCOPIA54LTR
CC   long terminal repeats, and by a 5-bp target-site duplication
CC   (AATTT).
CC   ATCOPIA54_I encodes remnants of the ATCOPIA54p Copia-like
CC   polyprotein. A long fragment of ATCOPIA54_I (positions 133-3949)
CC   is inverted in the genome and is flanked by a 80-bp inverted
CC   repeat (positions 53-132 and 3950-4029). The ATCOPIA54_I sequence
CC   reported here represents a reconstructed prototype of the
CC   ATCOPIA54
CC   provirus followed by the inversion. The reconstruction is defined
CC   below in DR lines.

XX
DR   [1] (Consensus)
XX
CC   ATCOPIA56_I is a consensus sequence of an internal region of
CC   ATCOPIA56
CC   Copia-like endogenous retrovirus. There are three copies of
CC   ATCOPIA56_I
CC   present in the genome; they are 99% identical to the consensus
CC   sequence,
CC   and are flanked by ~2% divergent ATCOPIA56LTR LTRs and 5-bp
CC   target-site
CC   duplications.
CC   ATCOPIA56_I encodes the 1358-aa ATCOPIA56p Copia-like
CC   polyprotein.
XX

OS   Arabidopsis thaliana

RA   Kapitonov V.V. and Jurka J.;
RT   "ATCOPIA58_I.";
RL   Repbase Reports 1(1), 18-18 (2001).
XX
DR   [1] (Consensus)
XX
CC   ATCOPIA58_I is a consensus sequence of an internal region of the
CC   ATCOPIA58 Copia-like endogenous retrovirus. There are 4 copies of
CC   ATCOPIA58_I present in the genome; they are 98% identical to the
CC   consensus sequence, and are flanked by ~1% divergent ATCOPIA58LTR
CC   LTRs and 5-bp target-site duplications.
CC   ATCOPIA58_I encodes the 1021-aa ATCOPIA58p Copia-like
CC   polyprotein.
CC   Presumably, ATCOPIA58 was a semi-autonomous endogenous
CC   retrovirus.
CC   It is ~85% identical to ENDOVIR1.
XX

RP   1-4231
RA   Kapitonov V.V. and Jurka J.;
RT   "Internal region of ATCOPIA66 copia-like LTR-retrotransposon - a
RT   consensus sequence.";
RL   Repbase Reports 1(2), 20-20 (2001).
XX
DR   [1] (Consensus)
XX
CC   ATCOPIA66_I is an internal region of the ATCOPIA66 Copia-like
CC   endogenous retrovirus flanked by the 1% divergent ATCOPIA66LTR
CC   long terminal repeats, and by a 5-bp target-site duplication.
CC   There are two copies of ATCOPIA66 present in the genome, they
CC   are 99% and 98% identical to the consensus sequence.
CC   ATCOPIA66's closest relative is 93% identical to the consensus
CC   sequence (ATCOPIA66A: AC007188, positions 36655-41067).
CC   ATCOPIA66_I encodes the 1372-aa Copia-like polyprotein
CC   ATCOPIA66p.
XX

CC   ATCOPIA68 was identified originally by [1]. Its boundaries
CC   were corrected by [2].
CC   ATCOPIA68_I is an internal region of the ATCOPIA68 Copia-like
CC   endogenous retrovirus flanked by the 9% divergent ATCOPIA68LTR
CC   long terminal repeats, and by a 5-bp target-site duplication.
CC   ATCOPIA68_I encodes well preserved remnants of the ATCOPIA68p
CC   Copia-like polyprotein.
XX

CC   ATCOPIA6 is a Copia-like retrovirus; its ORF encoding Copia-like
CC   polyprotein is not interrupted by any stop-codons; its LTRs are
CC   identical. We presume that ATCOPIA6 may be an active
CC   retroelement.
CC   Boundaries of ATCOPIA6I and ATCOPIA6LTR, originally reported by
CC   [1-2],
CC   have been changed [3] based on hallmarks of Copia-like elements.

CC   ATCOPIA76_I is an internal region of the ATCOPIA76 Copia-like
CC   endogenous retrovirus flanked by the 99% identical ATCOPIA76LTR
CC   long terminal repeats, and a 5-bp target-site duplication
CC   (GGTTT).
CC   ATCOPIA76_I encodes the 1361-aa ATCOPIA76p Copia-like polyprotein
CC   A corresponding CDS is interrupted by a copy of ATGP2NLTR, which
CC   is flanked by the GACAT target site duplication. The ATGP2NLTR
CC   and
CC   one the GACAT repeat were removed from the ATCOPIA76_I nucleotide
CC   sequence.

CC   ATCOPIA77_I is an internal region of the ATCOPIA77 Copia-like
CC   endogenous retrovirus flanked by the 97% identical ATCOPIA77LTR
CC   long terminal repeats, and a 5-bp target-site duplication
CC   (CTTTG).
CC   ATCOPIA77_I's CDS, which encodes remnants of the ATCOPIA77p
CC   Copia-like polyprotein, is slightly damaged by false stop codons
CC   and other mutations.
CC   ATENSPM1A transposon is inserted into ATCOPIA77_I and
CC   flanked by the CTA target site duplication. ATENSPM1A and the
CC   CTA repeat are removed from the ATCOPIA77_I sequence described
CC   here.
XX

DR   [1] (Consensus)
XX
CC   ATCOPIA78_I is a consensus sequence of an internal region of
CC   ATCOPIA78 Copia-like retroelement flanked by ~1% divergent LTRs,
CC   ATCOPIA78LTR, and 5 bp-long target-site duplicates.
CC   ATCOPIA78 is one of ~100 families of Copia-like
CC   LTR-retrotransposons,
CC   which were active in the A. thaliana genome during last 20 Myrs.
CC   The consensus sequence has been reconstructed based on eight
CC   copies present in the genome.
CC   These copies are ~99.4% identical to the consensus sequence.
CC   ATCOPIA78_I encodes ATCOPIA78p, a 1352-aa Copia-like polyprotein.
CC   It's possible that some copies of
CC   ATCOPIA78 are still active retrotransposons.
XX

XX
DR   GenBank; AC007915; Positions   54717   50376.
XX
CC   ATCOPIA79_I is an internal region of the ATCOPIA79 Copia-like
CC   endogenous retrovirus flanked by the 97% identical ATCOPIA79LTR
CC   long terminal repeats, and a 5-bp target-site duplication
CC   (CAAAG).
CC   ATCOPIA79_I encodes remnants of the ATCOPIA79p Copia-like
CC   polyprotein, which is slightly damaged by false stop codons
CC   and other mutations.
XX

XX
CC   ATCOPIA7 is a Copia-like retrovirus; its ORF encoding Copia-like
CC   polyprotein is not interrupted by any stop-codons; its LTRs,
CC   ATCOPIA7LTR, are 99% identical. We presume that ATCOPIA7 may be
CC   an active retrotransposon. ATCOPIA7 provirus is bordered by
CC   ACTTTC
CC   target-site duplication.
XX

CC   ATCOPIA80_I is an internal portion of the ATCOPIA80 Copia-like
CC   LTR-retrotransposon. It has been integrated in the A. thaliana
CC   genome
CC   more than 10 million years ago. There is only a 93% identity
CC   between
CC   long terminal repeats (ATCOPIA80LTR) that flank ATCOPIA80_I.
CC   The ATCOPIA80_I open reading frame that encoded originally a
CC   Copia-like polyprotein is damaged by numerous endogenous
CC   mutations.
XX

CC   ATCOPIA81_I is an internal region of the ATCOPIA81 Copia-like
CC   endogenous retrovirus flanked by the 98% identical ATCOPIA81LTR
CC   long terminal repeats, and a 5-bp target-site duplication
CC   (AACAT).
CC   ATCOPIA81 forms a separate family of Copia-like retroviruses
CC   present in the A. thaliana genome.
CC   ATCOPIA81_I encodes remnants of the ATCOPIA81p Copia-like
CC   polyprotein. The ORF which encodes ATCOPIA81p is slightly damaged
CC   by false stop codons.
XX

CC   ATCOPIA82_I is an internal region of the ATCOPIA82 Copia-like
CC   endogenous retrovirus flanked by the 98% identical ATCOPIA82LTR
CC   long terminal repeats, and a 5-bp target-site duplication
CC   (TTGGT).
CC   ATCOPIA82 forms a separate family of Copia-like retroviruses
CC   present in the A. thaliana genome.
CC   ATCOPIA82_I encodes (positions 14-4279) well preserved remnants
CC   of the ~1422-aa ATCOPIA82p Copia-like polyprotein. A false stop
CC   codons at position 1756 corresponds to H (based on polyproteins
CC   most close to ATCOPIA82p).

CC   ATCOPIA83_I is an internal region of the ATCOPIA83 Copia-like
CC   endogenous retrovirus flanked by the 99% identical ATCOPIA83LTR
CC   long terminal repeats, and a 5-bp target-site duplication
CC   (AGATA).
CC   ATCOPIA83 forms a separate family of Copia-like retroviruses
CC   present in the A. thaliana genome. There are two nearly identical
CC   copies of ATCOPIA83 found on chromosome 5. However one of them
CC   is a result of a ~14-kb duplication.
CC   ATCOPIA83 is most close to ATCOPIA26. There is a 74% identity
CC   between LTRs and internal portions of these two retroelements.
CC   ATCOPIA83_I encodes well preserved remnants of the ~1500-aa
CC   ATCOPIA83p Copia-like polyprotein.
CC   ATCOPIA83p (nucleotides at positions 982 and 983 form a false
CC   frame shift; we have deleted them to produce this polyprotein).
XX

CC   ATCOPIA84_I is an internal region of the ATCOPIA84 Copia-like
CC   endogenous retrovirus flanked by the 90% identical ATCOPIA84LTR
CC   long terminal repeats, and a 5-bp target-site duplication
CC   (GAGAA).
CC   ATCOPIA84 forms a separate family of Copia-like retroviruses
CC   present in the A. thaliana genome.
CC   ATCOPIA84_I encodes remnants of the ATCOPIA84p Copia-like
CC   polyprotein. The ORF which encodes ATCOPIA84p is damaged
CC   by multiple false stop codons and other mutations.

RT   "Internal portion of the ATCOPIA85 copia-like

DR   GenBank; AB025622; Positions   19551   23172.
XX
CC   ATCOPIA85_I is an internal region of the ATCOPIA85 Copia-like
CC   endogenous retrovirus.
CC   ATCOPIA85 forms a separate family of Copia-like retroviruses
CC   present in the A. thaliana genome. The only proviral copy
CC   is without the 5' LTR; approximately 1 kb of the internal portion
CC   is also lost. The 3' LTR is in place, we identified it based on
CC   a 95% identity to its copy present in AC023279.
CC   ATCOPIA85_I encodes remnants of the ATCOPIA85p Copia-like
CC   polyprotein. The ORF which encodes ATCOPIA85p does not have
CC   false stop codons. Therefore, ATCOPIA85 is a young retrovirus.
XX

CC   ATCOPIA86_I is an internal region of the ATCOPIA86 Copia-like
CC   endogenous retrovirus flanked by the 99% identical ATCOPIA86LTR
CC   long terminal repeats, and a 5-bp target-site duplication
CC   (TGTAG).
CC   ATCOPIA86 forms a separate family of Copia-like retroviruses
CC   present in the A. thaliana genome.
CC   ATCOPIA86_I encodes remnants of the ATCOPIA86p Copia-like
CC   polyprotein. The ORF which encodes ATCOPIA86p is damaged
CC   by one false frame shift.

CC   ATCOPIA88_I is an internal region of the ATCOPIA88 Copia-like
CC   endogenous retrovirus flanked by the 97% identical ATCOPIA88LTR
CC   long terminal repeats, and a 5-bp target-site duplication
CC   (TAATG).
CC   ATCOPIA88 forms a young family of Copia-like endogenous
CC   retroviruses
CC   present today in the A. thaliana genome.
CC   ATCOPIA88_I encodes remnants of the ATCOPIA88p Copia-like
CC   polyprotein. An ORF encoding the polyprotein is damaged
CC   by several false stop codons and frame shifts.

CC   ATCOPIA89_I is an internal region of the ATCOPIA89 Copia-like
CC   endogenous retrovirus flanked by the 99% identical ATCOPIA89LTR
CC   long terminal repeats. and a 5-bp target-site duplication
CC   (AACAT).
CC   ATCOPIA89 forms a separate family of Copia-like retroviruses
CC   present in the A. thaliana genome since members of other families
CC   are less than 75% identical to ATCOPIA89_I and ATCOPIA89LTR.
CC   ATCOPIA89_I (positions 91-4566) encodes remnants of the 1492-aa
CC   ATCOPIA89p Copia-like polyprotein. The ORF which encodes
CC   ATCOPIA89p is damaged by one false stop codon at position
CC   1690-1692 (marked by X in the ATCOPIA89p sequence).
XX

CC   ATCOPIA8A is a Copia-like retrovirus; its ORF encoding Copia-like
CC   polyprotein is not interrupted by any stop-codons; its LTRs are
CC   identical. We presume that ATCOPIA8 may be an active retroelement
CC   [3].
CC   ATCOPIA8A is 80% identical on the DNA level with ATCOPIA8B
CC   element.
CC   Since ATCOPIA8B is flanked by 99% identical LTRs and has
CC   preserved
CC   almost perfect ORF, we may say that both divergent forms,
CC   ATCOPIA8A
CC   and ATCOPIA8B have infected A.thaliana approximately at the same
CC   time [3]. Originally reported [1-2] LTR, internal region and 6
CC   bp-
CC   long target site are not correct [3]. ATCOPIA8, as a Copia-like
CC   retroelement, has 5 bp-long target site [3].
CC   343 bp-long 3' tail of ATCOPIA8AI is a perfect copy of the
CC   sequence
CC   followed by the ATCOPIA8A provirus. Based on the known LTRs from
CC   other ATCOPIAs, we consider this sequence as a part of the
CC   internal
CC   region [3].
XX

CC   ATCOPIA90_I is an internal region of the ATCOPIA90 Copia-like
CC   endogenous retrovirus flanked by the 99% identical ATCOPIA90LTR
CC   long terminal repeats and a 5-bp target-site duplication (GAAGC).
CC   ATCOPIA90 forms a separate family of Copia-like retroviruses
CC   present in the A. thaliana genome since members of other families
CC   are less than 75% identical to ATCOPIA90_I.
CC   ATCOPIA90_I (positions 442-4878) encodes remnants of the 1479-aa
CC   ATCOPIA90p Copia-like polyprotein. The ORF which encodes
CC   ATCOPIA90p is damaged by two false stop codons at positions
CC   2503-2505 and 3457-3459 (marked by Xs in the ATCOPIA90p
CC   sequence).
XX

CC   ATCOPIA91_I is an internal region of the ATCOPIA91 Copia-like
CC   endogenous retrovirus flanked by the 93% identical ATCOPIA91LTR
CC   long terminal repeats and a 5-bp target-site duplication (TTTTT).
CC   ATCOPIA91 forms a separate family of Copia-like retroviruses
CC   present in the A. thaliana genome since members of other families
CC   are less than 75% identical to ATCOPIA91_I.
CC   ATCOPIA91_I (positions 357-4973) encodes remnants of the ~1540-aa
CC   ATCOPIA91p Copia-like polyprotein. The ORF which encodes
CC   ATCOPIA91p is damaged by two indels that produce false frame
CC   shifts
CC   at positions 735 and 2162 (marked by Xs in the ATCOPIA91p
CC   sequence).
XX

CC   ATCOPIA92_I is an internal region of the ATCOPIA92 Copia-like
CC   endogenous retrovirus flanked by the 95% identical ATCOPIA92LTR
CC   long terminal repeats and a 5-bp target-site duplication (GAATA).
CC   ATCOPIA92 forms a separate family of Copia-like retroviruses
CC   present in the A. thaliana genome since members of other families
CC   are less than 75% identical to ATCOPIA92_I.
CC   ATCOPIA92_I encodes remnants of the ATCOPIA92p Copia-like
CC   polyprotein. The ORF which encodes ATCOPIA92p is damaged by
CC   several
CC   false frame shifts and stop codons.

CC   ATCOPIA93_I is an internal region of the ATCOPIA93 Copia-like
CC   endogenous retrovirus flanked by the 96% identical ATCOPIA93LTR
CC   long terminal repeats and a 5-bp target-site duplication (CAGCC).
CC   ATCOPIA93 forms a separate family of Copia-like retroviruses
CC   present in the A. thaliana genome since members of other families
CC   are less than 75% identical to ATCOPIA93_I.
CC   Chromosome 4 (AL161500, 110753-116088) harbors the ATCOPIA93A
CC   provirus whose identical LTRs and internal portion are 88% and
CC   91% identical to these in ATCOPIA93. ATCOPIA93A is a subfamily
CC   of ATCOPIA93.
CC   ATCOPIA93_I encodes remnants of the ATCOPIA93p Copia-like
CC   polyprotein. The ORF which encodes ATCOPIA93p is damaged by 5
CC   false stop codons and by 5 frame shifts induced by indels.
XX

CC   ATCOPIA94_I is an internal region of the ATCOPIA94 Copia-like
CC   endogenous retrovirus.
CC   ATCOPIA94 forms a separate family of Copia-like retroviruses
CC   present in the A. thaliana genome since members of other families
CC   are less than 75% identical to ATCOPIA94_I.
CC   ATCOPIA94_I encodes remnants of the ATCOPIA94p Copia-like
CC   polyprotein. The ORF which encodes ATCOPIA94p is damaged by
CC   one frame shift induced by a 5-bp deletion at position 3264
CC   (masked by XXXX in the 1436-aa ATCOPIA94p sequence).
CC   Such a low damage indicates that ATCOPIA94 has been
CC   retrotransposed
CC   recently.
CC   ATCOPIA94 is inserted exactly between two hypothetical genes
CC   that are 86% identical to each other.

DE   - a consensus sequence.
XX

KW   ATCOPIA95 family; ATCOPIA95LTR; ATCOPIA95_I; COPIA superfamily;
KW   LTR-retrotransposon; RIRE-1 group; internal region; pol;
KW   reverse transcriptase; internal portion.

NM   ATCOPIA95_I.
XX
OS   Arabidopsis thaliana
OC   Eukaryota; Viridiplantae; Streptophyta; Embryophyta; Tracheophyta;
OC   Spermatophyta; Magnoliophyta; eudicotyledons; Gunneridae;

OC   Camelineae; Arabidopsis.

RN   [1]
RP   1-5139
RA   Kapitonov V.V. and Jurka J.;
RT   "Internal portion of the ATCOPIA95 copia-like
RT   LTR-retrotransposon.";
RL   Repbase Reports 1(4), 6-6 (2001).
XX
DR   [1] (Consensus)
XX
CC   ATCOPIA95_I is a consensus sequence of an internal region of
CC   ATCOPIA95 Copia-like retroelement flanked by ~8% divergent LTRs,
CC   ATCOPIA95LTR, and 5 bp-long TSDs.
CC   ATCOPIA95 is one of ~100 families of Copia-like
CC   LTR-retrotransposons,
CC   which were active in the A. thaliana genome during last 20 Myrs.
CC   The consensus sequence has been reconstructed based on five
CC   copies present in the genome.
CC   These copies are ~95% identical to the consensus sequence.
CC   ATCOPIA95_I encodes ATCOPIA95p, a 1368-aa Copia-like polyprotein.
CC   The ATCOPIA95p ORFs in all ATCOPIA95_I copies present in the
CC   genome
CC   are damaged by false stop codons. There are no stop codons
CC   in the corresponding ORF in the consensus sequence.
CC   ATCOPIA95 is much closer to the rice RIRE1 Copia-like
CC   retrotransposons
CC   than to different arabidopsis Copia-like families.
CC   Internal portions of retrotransposons from other Copia families
CC   in the A. thaliana genome are less than 75% identical to
CC   ATCOPIA95_I.
CC   At the same time, the B. napa genome harbors a young Copia-like
CC   retrotransposon (AL245480, positions 39393 35143) whose 4.2-kb
CC   internal portion is 77% identical to ATCOPIA95_I. Presumably,
CC   ATCOPIA95-like Copia-like elements have invaded B. napa and
CC   A. thaliana independently (transmitted from other species).
XX

CC   ATCOPIA96_I is an internal portion of the ATCOPIA96 Copia-like
CC   LTR retrotransposon flanked by 5% divergent LTRs, ATCOPIA96LTR,
CC   and 5 bp-long TSDs (AAATA).
CC   ATCOPIA96 is one of ~100 families of Copia-like
CC   LTR-retrotransposons,
CC   which were active in the A. thaliana genome during last 20 Myrs.
CC   ATCOPIA88 is the closest family to ATCOPIA96; there is only a 72%
CC   identity between ATCOPIA88_I and ATCOPIA96_I.
CC   A few false stop-codons and frameshifts have damaged ORF which
CC   encoded originally an intact Copia-like polyprotein.
XX

DR   [2] (Consensus)
XX
CC   Target sites and TIRs are similar to those of ATDNA12T3A and it
CC   was originally classified as a DNA transposon. However, the
CC   sequence is composed of LTR-like repeats that include a fragment
CC   of 5S rRNA. Furthermore, the internal region contains a tRNA-like
CC   sequence and many elements are flanked by 5 bp TSDs
CC   characteristic for Copia-type retrotransposons. Therefore, the
CC   sequence is re-classified as a
CC   non-autonomous LTR retrotransposon.

DR   GenBank; AL137079; Positions   48998   51369.
XX
CC   ATDNA12T3A is a non-autonomous DNA transposon from unknown
CC   superfamily.
CC   It has 12-bp terminal inverted repeats and is flanked by 3-bp
CC   target site duplication. Harbinger and En/Spm are two known
CC   classes
CC   of autonomous DNA transposons whose transposases generate 3-bp
CC   target
CC   site duplications in the A. thaliana genome. However, its
CC   unlikely
CC   that ATDNA12T3A belongs to one of these classes since it has
CC   completely different terminal inverted repeats.
CC   This particular copy was found as an insertion into a copy of
CC   of the ATHILA6 retrovirus (chromosome 3). A second, 87%
CC   identical,
CC   copy is present in chromosome 4 (AL16150, position 82230 -
CC   79733).
XX

DR   [1] (Consensus)
XX
CC   ATDNA1T9A is a nonautonomous DNA transposon. There are several
CC   copies of this element in the genome, they are 99% identical to
CC   the consensus sequence. ATDNA1T9A is flanked by 9-bp target site
CC   duplications generated upon its integration in the genome.
CC   ATDNA1T9A shares common ~100-bp termini with LIMPET, ATDNAI27T9A,
CC   VANDAL4 and VANDAL5 transposons (~65% identity).
CC   An autonomous transposon involved in a proliferation of ATDNA1T9A
CC   is related to the superfamily of VANDAL-like megatransposons.
CC   ATDNA1T9A harbors the host phosphate/phosphoenolpyruvate
CC   translocator (PPT) gene (GenBank AF209210). The ATDNA1T9A second
CC   strand (position 2743-3274) is 93% identical with truncated
CC   PPT exon 1, intron 3 and exon 5, and complete exon 4 and intron
CC   4.
CC   The genome contains a few copies of the ATDNA1T9B transposon,
CC   which is free of the PPT gene and is an ancestor of ATDNA1T9A.
XX

CC   ATDNA2T9A is a non-autonomous DNA transposon.
CC   ATDNA2T9A copies are flanked by 9-bp target site duplications
CC   generated upon its integration in the genome.
CC   There are 4 copies of ATDNA2T9A in the genome; one of them is 95%
CC   and the other three copies are 99% identical to the consensus
CC   sequence, respectively.

DR   [1] (Consensus)
XX
CC   ATDNA2T9B is a non-autonomous DNA transposon. ATDNA2T9B copies
CC   are flanked by 9-bp target site duplications generated upon its
CC   integration in the genome. There are 3 copies of ATDNA2T9B in the
CC   genome; they are 99% identical to the ATDNA2T9B consensus
CC   sequence. An autonomous transposon involved in a proliferation of
CC   ATDNA2T9B is expected to be related to VANDAL-like
CC   megatransposons. A left arm of the ATDNA2T9B consensus sequence,
CC   position 1-915, is ~100% identical to the corresponding arm of
CC   the ATDNA2T9A consensus sequence. However, there is only a 67%
CC   identity between the remaining portions of the ATDNA2T9A and
CC   ATDNA2T9B consensus sequences.
XX

XX

XX
DE   Non-autonomous DNA transposon ATDNAI26T9 - a consensus sequence.
XX
KW   MuDR; DNA transposon; Transposable Element; Nonautonomous; ARNOLD;
KW   ATDNAI26T9; VANDAL; nonautonomous DNA transposon.
XX
OS   Arabidopsis thaliana
OC   Eukaryota; Viridiplantae; Streptophyta; Embryophyta; Tracheophyta;
OC   Spermatophyta; Magnoliophyta; eudicotyledons; Gunneridae;
OC   Pentapetalae; rosids; malvids; Brassicales; Brassicaceae;
OC   Camelineae; Arabidopsis.
XX
RN   [1]
RP   1-2432
RA   Kapitonov V.V. and Jurka J.;
RT   "ATDNAI26T9.";
RL   Direct Submission to Repbase Update (FEB-2001).
XX
DR   [1] (Consensus)
XX
CC   ATDNAI26T9 is a nonautonomous DNA transposon. There are five
CC   copies of this element in the genome, they are ~99% identical to
CC   the consensus sequence. ATDNAI26T9 is flanked by imperfect
CC   26-bp terminal inverted repeats, and it has generated 9 bp
CC   target site duplications upon its integration in the genome.
CC   An autonomous transposon involved in a proliferation of
CC   ATNDAI26T9A
CC   is related to the superfamily of megatransposons ARNOLD and
CC   VANDAL
CC   elements, which encode MuDR-like transposase.
XX

CC   copies of this element in the genome, they are 99% identical to
CC   the consensus sequence. ATDNAI27T9A is flanked by imperfect
CC   27 bp terminal inverted repeats, and it generates 9 bp
CC   target site duplications upon its integration in the genome.

CC   ARNOLD and VANDAL elements.

CC   ATDNAI27T9B is a nonautonomous DNA transposon. There are ~20
CC   copies of this element in the genome, they are 90% identical to
CC   the consensus sequence. ATDNAI27T9B is flanked by imperfect
CC   27 bp terminal inverted repeats, and it generates 9 bp
CC   target site duplications upon its integration in the genome.
CC   An autonomous transposon involved in a proliferation of
CC   ATNDAI27T9B
CC   is related to the superfamily of megatransposons which includes
CC   ARNOLD and VANDAL elements.

DR   [1] (Consensus)
XX
CC   ATENSPM1 is an autonomous DNA transposon from En/Spm superfamily.
CC   Its individual copies are ~99% identical to the consensus
CC   sequence. They are bordered by 3 bp-long target site
CC   duplications.
CC   ATENSPM1 has 29 bp-long perfect TIRs. Transposase encoded by
CC   ATENSPM1 is most close to the transposase encoded by PSL
CC   transposon
CC   found in the petunia genome.
XX

RP   1-8272
RA   Kapitonov V.V.;
RT   "ATENSPM10.";
RL   Direct Submission to Repbase Update (MAY-2001).
XX
DR   [1] (Consensus)
XX
CC   ATENSPM10 is an autonomous DNA transposon from En/Spm
CC   superfamily.
CC   It was transpositionally active in the genome several million
CC   years
CC   ago. There are ~20 copies of this transposon present in the
CC   genome.
CC   They are ~95% identical to the consensus sequence.
CC   ATENSPM10 elements have generated 3-bp target site duplications
CC   upon their insertion in the genome.
CC   ATENSPM10 has 28-bp TIRs. The consensus sequence has been
CC   reconstructed based on multiple alignment of 12 copies. These
CC   copies
CC   belong to different minor subfamilies.
CC   ATENSPM10 encodes ATENSPM10p, a transposase-like 1771-aa
CC   proteins. The protein is encoded by putative 14 exons, predicted
CC   by FGENESH (http://www.softberry.com/nucleo.html):
CC   1 + 1 CDSf 1201 - 2631 132.14 1201 - 2631 1431
CC   1 + 2 CDSi 2914 - 3539 65.37 2914 - 3537 624
CC   1 + 3 CDSi 3618 - 3905 36.61 3619 - 3903 285
CC   1 + 4 CDSi 4027 - 4096 -6.14 4028 - 4096 69
CC   1 + 5 CDSi 4165 - 4759 52.03 4165 - 4758 594
CC   1 + 6 CDSi 4908 - 4951 11.66 4910 - 4951 42
CC   1 + 7 CDSi 4999 - 5568 93.49 4999 - 5568 570
CC   1 + 8 CDSi 5639 - 5845 24.76 5639 - 5845 207
CC   1 + 9 CDSi 5912 - 6001 11.13 5912 - 6001 90
CC   1 + 10 CDSi 6081 - 6188 9.19 6081 - 6188 108
CC   1 + 11 CDSi 6259 - 6513 38.17 6259 - 6513 255
CC   1 + 12 CDSi 6594 - 6935 39.42 6594 - 6935 342
CC   1 + 13 CDSi 7024 - 7365 17.15 7024 - 7365 342
CC   1 + 14 CDSl 7479 - 7766 28.00 7479 - 7766 288
CC   1 + PolA 8123 1.05.
XX

AC   AB028618;
XX
DT   27-DEC-2001 (Rel. 6.11, Created)
DT   27-DEC-2001 (Rel. 6.11, Last updated, Version 1)
XX
DE   ATENSPM11 is a fossilized DNA transposon.
XX
KW   EnSpm/CACTA; DNA transposon; Transposable Element; ATENSPM11;
KW   ATENSPM11 family; En/Spm superfamily; TIR; transposase.
XX
OS   Arabidopsis thaliana
OC   Eukaryota; Viridiplantae; Streptophyta; Embryophyta; Tracheophyta;
OC   Spermatophyta; Magnoliophyta; eudicotyledons; Gunneridae;
OC   Pentapetalae; rosids; malvids; Brassicales; Brassicaceae;
OC   Camelineae; Arabidopsis.
XX
RN   [1]
RP   1-8144
RA   Kapitonov V.V. and Jurka J.;
RT   "Molecular fossil of the ATENSP11 family.";
RL   Repbase Reports 1(4), 7-7 (2001).
XX
DR   GenBank; AB028618; Positions     953    9096.
XX
CC   ATENSPM11 is a family of fossilized DNA transposons that belong
CC   to the En/Spm superfamily.
CC   Only two copies of ATENSPM11 are present in the A. thaliana
CC   genome,
CC   they are 95% identical to each other. The second copy is harbored
CC   by chromosome 4 and it is severely damaged by two long deletions.
CC   The first copy, deposited in Repbase, has been inserted recently
CC   into
CC   ATHILA7LTR copy, it is flanked by the GAT target site
CC   duplication.
CC   ATENSPM11 has 29-bp imperfect terminal inverted repeats and
CC   encodes
CC   an En/Spm-like transposase by several exons. Some of them are
CC   damaged
CC   by a few false stop codons.
XX

DR   [1] (Consensus)
XX
CC   ATENSPM1A is an autonomous DNA transposon from the En/Spm
CC   superfamily. Its individual copies are ~98% identical to the
CC   consensus sequence. Five copies of ATENSPM1A are present in the
CC   genome. They are bordered by 3 bp-long target site duplications.
CC   ATENSPM1A has 29-bp TIRs. There is a 84% identity
CC   between the ATENSPM1A and ATENSPM1 consensus sequences.
CC   ATENSPM1A encodes two proteins: ATENSPM1A1p (CDS: 1434-947 and
CC   231-96) and ATENSPM1A2p (CDS: 1584-1855, 2073-2199, 2277-2567,
CC   2664-2885 and 3402-3776). Function and classification of
CC   ATENSPM1A1p is unknown. ATENSPM1A2p is a transposase.
XX

CC   ATENSPM2 is an autonomous DNA transposon from En/Spm superfamily.
CC   Its individual copies are ~95% identical to each other.
CC   They are bordered by 15-bp TIRs and 3 bp-long target site
CC   duplications.
CC   Two putative proteins are encoded by multiple exons.

CC   ATENSPM3 is an autonomous DNA transposon from En/Spm superfamily.
CC   Its individual copies are ~98% identical to each other.
CC   They are bordered by 3 bp-long target site duplications.
CC   Two putative proteins are encoded by multiple exons.

XX
CC   ATENSPM4 is an autonomous DNA transposon from En/Spm superfamily.
CC   Its individual copies are >90% identical to each other.
CC   They are bordered by 32-bp TIRs and a 3-bp target site
CC   duplication.
CC   Transposase is encoded by several exons. ATENSPM4 is ~70%
CC   identical to ATENSPM1 and ATENSPM2 transposons. All
CC   these transposons are young despite the low identity.
XX

CC   ATENSPM6 is an autonomous DNA transposon from En/Spm superfamily.
CC   Its individual copies are ~99% identical to the consensus
CC   sequence. They are bordered by 3 bp-long target site
CC   duplications.
CC   ATENSPM6 has perfect 18 bp TIRs.
CC   A putative transposase is encoded by six exons (258-2664;
CC   2739-3087; 3152-3331; 3408-3507; 3588-3978; 4055-4374):
CC   MAGNYNYGGTGGFYRDWMYKRFDEVTGNLSAEYVAGVEQFMTFANSQPIVQSSRGKFHCP
CC   CSVCKNEKHIISGRRVSSHLFSHGFMPDYYVWYKHGEEMNMDIGTSYTNRTYFSENHEEV
CC   GNIVEDPYVDMVNDAFNFNVGYDDNYRHDDSYQNVEEPVRNHSNKFYDLLEGANNPLYDG
CC   CREGQSQLSLASRLMHNKAEYNMSEKLVDSVCEMFTDFLPEGNQATTSHYQTEKLMRNLG
CC   LPYHTIDVCQNNCMLFWKEDEKEDQCRFCGAKRWKPKDDRRRTKVPYSRMWYLPIGDRLK
CC   RMYQSHKTAAAMRWHAEHQSKEGEMNHPSDAAEWRYFQGLHPQFAEEPRNVYLGLCTDGF
CC   NPFGMSRNHSLWPVILTPYNLPPGMCMNTEYLFLTILNSGPNHPRASLDVFLQPLIEELK
CC   ELWSTGVDAYDVSLSQNFNLKAVLLWTISDFPAYSMLSGWTTHGKLSCPVCMESTKSFYL
CC   PNGRKTCWFDCHRRFLPHGHPSRRNRKDFLKGRDASSEYPPESLTGEQVYYERLASVNPP
CC   KTKDVGGNGHEKKMRGYGKEHNWHKESILWELSYWKDLNLRHNIDVMHTEKNFLDNIMNT
CC   LMRVKGKSKDNIMSRLDIEKFCSRPGLHIDSSGKAPFPAYTLTEEAKQSLLQCVKYDIRF
CC   PDGYSSDLASCVDLDNGKFSGMKSHDCHVFMERLLPFIFAELLDRNVHLALSGIGAFFRD
CC   LCSRTLQTSRVQILKQNIVLIICNLEKIFPPSFFDVMEHLPIHLPYEAELGGPVQYRWMY
CC   PFERFFKKLKGKAKNKRYAAGSIVESYINDEIAYFSEHYFADHIQTKSRLTRFNEGEVPV
CC   YHVPGVPNIFMHVGRPSGEMHVDWLSEKDYQSAHAYVLRNCDYFKPFESMFEDYLSAKYP
CC   CLPEKELYARRAEEYHLWVKEYVTYWNTTSPFPTWVQEIVQGPLNKVKTWPMYFTRGYLF
CC   HTQNHGAGRKTCNYGVCVKGENYADSSDEADFYGTLTDIIELEYEGIVNLRITLFKCKWY

CC   FRCNLSSSDEDEVEDEDV
CC   Second protein, similar to PttA, Tnp1 and gene 1 proteins
CC   from petunia, snapdragon and maize Em/Spm-like transposons,
CC   is encoded by five exons (5425-5942; 6732-6894; 6950-7237;
CC   7342-7569; 7651-8013):
CC   MPIAGRGGSRKRKTTPNVTQRAGAGGSRPANLPPQYNFTPAPAVQVPATEPAQQHGPSTS

CC   ATENSPM7 is an autonomous DNA transposon from En/Spm superfamily.
CC   Its individual copies are ~95% identical to each other.
CC   ATENSPM7 is 76% identical with ATENSPM3.
CC   ATENSPM7 has 22-bp TIRs and is flanked by 3-bp target site
CC   duplication. ATENSPM7 encodes the 1675-aa ATENSPM7p protein by
CC   16 exons. ATENSPM7p has the Em/Spm-like transposase domain.
CC   CDS join(1112..1143,1228..2136,2230..2905,2999..3264,
CC   3713..3737,3804..3997,4077..4186,43151..4862,
CC   5150..5494,5577..5780,6025..6132,6208..6459,
CC   6541..6579,6667..6966,7062..7521,7669..7904).

CC   ATENSPM8 is a fossilized DNA transposon from En/Spm superfamily.
CC   It is present as a single copy inserted into VANDAL3-like
CC   transposon and flanked by 3-bp target-site duplication.
CC   ATENSPM8 has 13-bp terminal inverted repeats and encodes
CC   an incomplete En/Spm-like transposase, ATENSPM8p.
CC   ATENSPM8 harbors a non-autonomous derivative of the ATHPOGO
CC   transposon, which is cut from the sequence reported here.
XX

CC   ATENSPM9 is an autonomous DNA transposon from En/Spm superfamily.
CC   Its individual copies are ~96% identical to the consensus
CC   sequence. They are bordered by 3 bp-long target site
CC   duplications.
CC   ATENSPM9 has perfect 13-bp TIRs. The consensus sequence has been
CC   reconstructed based on 5 copies. These copies form two minor
CC   subfamilies. ATENSPM9 encodes two proteins, ATENSPM9p1 and
CC   ATENSPMp2. ATENSPMp1 is a 1147-aa transposase encoded by six
CC   exons (673-2848, 2917-3265, 3340-3519, 3608-3707, 3924-4191,
CC   4232-4602).
CC   ATENSPMp1:

CC   ATGP10_I is an internal portion of ATGP10, a Gypsy-like
CC   retrovirus which was integrated into the genome long time ago;
CC   its LTRs
CC   (deposited in Repbase as ATGP10LTR) are 90% identical to each
CC   other.
CC   Two ORFs, which have encoded GAG and POL polyproteins, are
CC   saturated
CC   by false stop codons and frame shifts.

CC   ATGP1I is an internal part of ATGP1 LTR-retrotransposon;
CC   its LTR is deposited as ATGP1LTR. Presumably, ATGP1
CC   retrotransposon was an active element several millions years ago.
CC   ATGP1 proviruses and solo LTRs are bordered by 5 bp-long target
CC   site duplications.
CC   The consensus sequence has been reconstructed based on 13
CC   individual
CC   copies present in the GenBank 109.0 release. There are two major
CC   subfamilies of ATGP1. Retroelements from the first subfamily
CC   are ~97% identical to each other; the second subfamily is a
CC   little
CC   bit older since its copies have 95% mutual identity. There is
CC   ~92%
CC   identity between sequences from different subfamilies. Examples
CC   of
CC   the first subfamily include copies found in AB01821 and AC002534
CC   GenBank loci; copies found in AF0588825 and AC006268 represent
CC   the
CC   second subfamily. There is 97% identity between consensus
CC   sequences
CC   reconstructed for each of these subfamilies.
CC   Two gag- and pol-like polyproteins are encoded by separate ORF1
CC   (position 253-1629) and ORF2 (position 1669-5067). ORF1 codes for
CC   two Zn-finger CCHC-type domains (aa positions 362-375 and
CC   384-400)
CC   analogously to gag-like proteins in many retroviruses including
CC   HIV2
CC   and caulimovirus.
XX

RN   [3]
RA   Kapitonov V.V. and Jurka J.;
RT   "Molecular paleontology of transposable elements from Arabidopsis
RT   thaliana.";
RL   Genetica 107(1-3), 27-37 (1999).
XX
DR   [2] (Consensus)
XX
CC   ATGP1LTR is a long terminal repeat from the ATGP1
CC   LTR-retrotransposon. An internal part flanked by ATGP1LTR is
CC   deposited as ATGP1I.
CC   The consensus sequence has been reconstructed based on 30
CC   individual
CC   copies present in the GenBank 109.0 release. There are two major
CC   subfamilies of ATGP1LTR. Sequences from the first subfamily
CC   are ~97% identical to each other; the second subfamily is a
CC   little
CC   bit older since its copies have 95% mutual identity. There is
CC   ~92%
CC   identity between sequences from different subfamilies. Examples
CC   of
CC   the first subfamily include copies found in AB01821 and AC002534
CC   GenBank loci; copies found in AF0588825 and AC006268 represent
CC   the
CC   second subfamily. There is 97% identity between consensus
CC   sequences
CC   reconstructed for each of these subfamilies.
XX

CC   ATGP2I is an internal region of a gag-pol LTR-retrotransposon,
CC   ATGP2, that was active recently since there is only 1% divergence
CC   between its LTRs, ATGP2LTR. ATGP2 provirus is bordered by 5
CC   bp-long
CC   target-site duplication. ATGP2I's ORF1 and ORF2 encode gag and
CC   pol-like polyproteins.
XX

CC   ATGP2N_I is an internal portion of the ATGP2N nonautonomous
CC   LTR retrotransposon. Its long terminal repeat is deposited
CC   in Repbase Update as ATGP2NLTR.
CC   There are more than 5 copies of ATGP2N_I in the genome;
CC   they are ~97% identical to the consensus sequence.
CC   ATGP2N_I shares the same PBS with ATGP2I. The last one was
CC   likely related to transpositions of ATGP2N.

RT   thaliana.";

XX
DR   [1] (Consensus)
XX
CC   ATHAT10 is an ancient autonomous hAT-like DNA transposon.
CC   There are several copies of ATHAT10 present in the genome.
CC   They are ~95% identical with the consensus sequence.
CC   ATHAT10 has 12-bp terminal inverted repeats and encodes the
CC   ~670-aa ATHAT10p transposase (there is one false frame shift at
CC   position ~1350).
CC   The ATHATN10 DNA transposon is a nonautonomous derivative of
CC   ATHAT10.
CC   CDS join(884..2869).
XX

XX
DR   GenBank; AL132953; Positions   34952   31380.
XX
CC   ATHAT2 is a fossilized HAT-like autonomous DNA transposon.
CC   There are at least two almost complete copies of
CC   the transposon fossilized in the genome. They are 93% identical
CC   to each other.
CC   ATHAT2 is flanked by 8-bp target site duplications.
CC   ATHAT2 has 14-bp terminal inverted repeats and encodes the
CC   656-aa ATHAT2p transposase.
CC   CDS join(349..414,742..1098,1204..1615,1697..1978,
CC   2041..2871,2960..2982)
CC   The ATHAT2 70-bp 5' and 140-bp 3' termini are ~70% identical
CC   with corresponding termini of the non-autonomous transposons
CC   ATHATN1-ATHATN5.
XX

CC   ATHAT3 is a recently active autonomous HAT-like DNA transposon.
CC   There are three copies of ATHAT3 present in the genome.
CC   They are ~96% identical with each other. Only this particular
CC   copy preserved nearly complete transposase, two other
CC   copies harbor only C-terminal portions of the transposase.
CC   ATHAT3 has 11-bp terminal inverted repeats and encodes the
CC   749-aa ATHAT3p transposase. ATHAT3 is flanked by 8-bp target
CC   site duplication.
CC   DNA transposon ATHATN3 is a non-autonomous derivative of ATHAT3.
CC   CDS join(260..356,1205..3350).

CC   ATHAT7 is a recently active autonomous HAT-like DNA transposon.
CC   There are two copies of ATHAT7 present in the genome.
CC   They are 97% identical with each other.
CC   ATHAT7 has 14-bp terminal inverted repeats and encodes the
CC   750-aa ATHAT7p transposase. ATHAT7 copies are flanked by 8-bp
CC   target site duplication.
CC   DNA transposon ATHATN7 is a non-autonomous derivative of
CC   a transposon related closely to ATHAT7. The ATHAT7 and ATHATN7
CC   consensus sequences share ~80% identical ~180-bp 5' and
CC   3' termini, respectively.
CC   CDS join(604..2827).

CC   It's a HAT-like nonautonomous DNA transposon flanked

CC   copies of ATHATN1 in the genome. The ATHATN1 portions 22-164
CC   and 86-237 are 80% identical to each other.

DR   [1] (Consensus)
XX
CC   ATHILA0_I is an internal portion of the ATHILA0 endogenous
CC   retrovirus. There are several copies of ATHILA0 in the genome;
CC   they are ~95% identical to the consensus sequence. Long terminal
CC   repeats from ATHILA0 are 94% identical with ATHILA3_LTR.
CC   ATHILA0 has generated 5-bp target site duplications.
CC   ATHILA0 encodes the Gypsy-like pol polyprotein, which
CC   includes protease, reverse transcriptase and RNAse H and
CC   integrase.
CC   ATHILA0_I encodes two proteins, ATHILA0p1 and ATHILA0p2.

CC   EAPDNEERVESEEGAENEEGEEMDWENYNASRFHFEEHKPPPRVSKSLTVAHKNIGSMSA
CC   WNKFQDKMLEKCGKAIAAIQAVLSCSSSGATMVRENRPEEVVSRRHRVSPSRQSAYEQRE
CC   VSRPQAPARHSSHEHREQKRRRKTRIVRPRSKDLLMSSRRSLDQDTRRDIEQSVEQDPWV
CC   QNEQSVEQNQWDQDGQYSGMNWDAYHGINEQEPTSDN
CC   Presumably, ATHILA0-like retroelements have been acting as
CC   autonomous retroelements. ATHILA3 share 94% identical
CC   LTRs with ATHILA0. Putatively, ATHILA3 is a non-autonomous
CC   derivate of ATHILA0-like element. Their internal sequences,
CC   ATHILA0_I and ATHILA3_I, are 91% and 95% identical over 1700-bp
CC   3'- and 2600-bp 5'-flanks. The remaining portion of ATHILA3_I
CC   encodes "non-retroviral" protein sequences related to these
CC   present in the previously reported ATHILAs.
CC   A close relative of ATHILA0 is present in Vicia faba (GenBank
CC   GI: 2522228; 69% protein identity over 400 aa).

CC   ATHILA2I is an internal portion of ATHILA2 endogenous retrovirus.
CC   It belongs to the Gypsy superfamily and is related to the ATHILA
CC   retrovirus. ATHILA2 copies are ~95% identical to each other and
CC   ~75% identical to the ATHILA elements. ATHILA2_I is flanked
CC   by the ATHILA2_LTR long terminal repeats.
XX

CC   ATHILA3I is an internal portion of ATHILA3 endogenous retrovirus.
CC   It belongs to the Gypsy superfamily and is related to the ATHILA
CC   retrovirus. ATHILA3 copies are ~95% identical to each other and
CC   ~70% identical to the ATHILA and ATHILA2 elements. ATHILA3_I is
CC   flanked by the ATHILA3_LTR long terminal repeats.

XX
DR   [1] (Consensus)
XX
CC   ATHILA4A_I is an internal portion of the ATHILA4A endogenous
CC   retrovirus. There are several copies of ATHILA4A_I in the genome;
CC   they are ~93% identical with the consensus sequence.
CC   Apparently, ATHILA4A is a non-autonomous element; its internal
CC   portion encodes one protein, ATHILA4Ap, which is related to
CC   the "ORF1" proteins encoded by ATHILA and retroviruses expressed
CC   in Vicia faba cells (GenBank GI: 7488857 and 2522227).
CC   ATHILA4A was active in the A.thaliana genome relatively recently
CC   since its proviral copies are flanked by 89-97% identical LTRs.
CC   There is ~80% identity between 160-bp 5' ends of ATHILA4A_I
CC   and ATHILA4_I.
XX

XX
CC   ATHILA4B_LTR is a long terminal repeat from the ATHILA4B
CC   endogenous
CC   retrovirus. There are about 30 copies of ATHILA4B_LTR in the
CC   genome;
CC   they are ~95% identical with the consensus sequence.
CC   Solo LTRs are flanked by 5-bp target-site duplications.
CC   ATHILA4B_LTR is 77% identical with both ATHILA4A_LTR and
CC   ATHILA4_LTR.

KW   Gypsy; LTR Retrotransposon; Transposable Element;
KW   Athila superfamily; ATHILA4C_I; ATHILA4C_LTR; ATHILA6B_I;
KW   Gypsy-like endogenous retrovirus; integrase; protease;
KW   reverse transcriptase; internal portion.

OS   Arabidopsis thaliana
OC   Eukaryota; Viridiplantae; Streptophyta; Embryophyta; Tracheophyta;

RN   [1]
RP   1-8639
RA   Kapitonov V.V. and Jurka J.;
RT   "ATHILA4C_I.";
RL   Direct Submission to Repbase Update (MAY-2001).
XX
DR   [1] (Consensus)
XX
CC   ATHILA4C_I is an internal part of the ATHILA4C endogenous
CC   retrovirus. There are ~10 copies of ATHILA4C_I in the genome;
CC   they are ~94% identical to the consensus sequence. The consensus
CC   sequence was derived from 10 proviral copies. These copies are
CC   flanked by ~96% identical LTRs (ATHILA4C_LTR). They have
CC   generated
CC   5-bp target site duplications upon their integration into the
CC   genome. ATHILA4C_I sequences can be split further into
CC   minor subfamilies.
CC   ATHILA4C_I encodes two proteins: 1772-aa ATHILA4C1p (positions
CC   155-5473) and 499-aa ATHILA4C2p (positions 5863-7362).
CC   ATHILA4C1p is composed of the retroviral gag-like, protease,
CC   reverse
CC   transcriptase and integrase domains.
XX

DR   [1] (Consensus)
XX
CC   ATHILA4C_LTR is a long terminal repeat from the ATHILA4C
CC   endogenous
CC   retrovirus. There are about 20 copies of ATHILA4C_LTR in the
CC   genome;
CC   they are ~94% identical to the consensus sequence. ATHILA4C is
CC   even
CC   younger that is expected given the 6% divergence since its copies
CC   belong to different minor subfamilies.
CC   Solo LTRs and proviral copies are flanked by 5-bp target-site
CC   duplications.

CC   retrovirus. There are several copies of ATHILA5 in the genome;

CC   repeats from ATHILA5 are deposited in Repbase Update as
CC   ATHILA5_LTR. ATHILA5 has generated 5-bp target site duplications.
CC   ATHILA5_I encodes two proteins, ATHILA5p1 and ATHILA5p2.

ID   ATHILA6A_I  repbase;    DNA;    PLN; 7835 BP.
XX
AC   .
XX
DT   17-MAY-2001 (Rel. 6.04, Created)
DT   17-MAY-2001 (Rel. 6.04, Last updated, Version 1)
XX
DE   ATHILA6A_I is a an internal part of the ATHILA6A endogenous
DE   retrovirus - a consensus sequence.
XX
KW   Gypsy; LTR Retrotransposon; Transposable Element;
KW   Athila superfamily; ATHILA6A_I; ATHILA6A_LTR; ATHILA6B_I;
KW   Gypsy-like endogenous retrovirus; integrase; Long terminal repeat;
KW   reverse transcriptase; internal portion.
XX
OS   Arabidopsis thaliana
OC   Eukaryota; Viridiplantae; Streptophyta; Embryophyta; Tracheophyta;
OC   Spermatophyta; Magnoliophyta; eudicotyledons; Gunneridae;
OC   Pentapetalae; rosids; malvids; Brassicales; Brassicaceae;
OC   Camelineae; Arabidopsis.
XX
RN   [1]
RP   1-7835
RA   Kapitonov V.V.;
RT   "ATHILA6A_I.";
RL   Direct Submission to Repbase Update (MAY-2001).
XX
DR   [1] (Consensus)
XX
CC   ATHILA6A_I is an internal part of the ATHILA6A endogenous
CC   retrovirus. There are several copies of ATHILA6A_I in the genome;
CC   they are ~99% identical to the consensus sequence. The consensus
CC   sequence was derived from 5 proviral copies. These copies are
CC   flanked by 99% identical LTRs (ATHILA6A_LTR). They have generated
CC   5-bp target site duplications upon their integration into the
CC   genome.
CC   ATHILA6A_I encodes two proteins: 911-aa ATHILA6A1p (positions
CC   173-2905) and 648-aa ATHILA6A2p (positions 4237-6180).
CC   ATHILA6A_I and ATHILA6B_I share identical ~1400-bp and ~1850-bp
CC   3'- and 5' ends, respectively. However, their central portions
CC   (positions 2400-5970 in ATHILA6A_I) are not similar to each
CC   other.
CC   Since, the central portion of ATHILA6B_I encodes the reverse
CC   transcriptase and integrase, ATHILA6A was a non-autonomous
CC   retroelement, whose transposition was mediated by ATHILA6B.
XX

DR   [1] (Consensus)
XX
CC   ATHILA6A_LTR is a long terminal repeat from the ATHILA6A
CC   endogenous
CC   retrovirus. There are about 50 copies of ATHILA6A_LTR in the
CC   genome;
CC   they are ~97% identical to the consensus sequence. ATHILA6A is
CC   even
CC   younger that is expected given the 3% divergence since its copies
CC   belong to different subfamilies.
CC   Solo LTRs and proviral copies are flanked by 5-bp target-site
CC   duplications.
XX

ID   ATHILA6B_I  repbase;    DNA;    PLN; 7963 BP.
XX
AC   .
XX
DT   17-MAY-2001 (Rel. 6.04, Created)
DT   17-MAY-2001 (Rel. 6.04, Last updated, Version 1)
XX
DE   ATHILA6B_I is a an internal part of the ATHILA6B endogenous
DE   retrovirus - a consensus sequence.
XX
KW   Gypsy; LTR Retrotransposon; Transposable Element;
KW   Athila superfamily; ATHILA6A_I; ATHILA6A_LTR; ATHILA6B_I;
KW   Gypsy-like endogenous retrovirus; integrase; Long terminal repeat;
KW   reverse transcriptase; internal portion.
XX
OS   Arabidopsis thaliana
OC   Eukaryota; Viridiplantae; Streptophyta; Embryophyta; Tracheophyta;
OC   Spermatophyta; Magnoliophyta; eudicotyledons; Gunneridae;
OC   Pentapetalae; rosids; malvids; Brassicales; Brassicaceae;
OC   Camelineae; Arabidopsis.
XX
RN   [1]
RP   1-7963
RA   Kapitonov V.V.;
RT   "ATHILA6B_I.";
RL   Direct Submission to Repbase Update (MAY-2001).
XX
DR   [1] (Consensus)
XX
CC   ATHILA6B_I is an internal part of the ATHILA6A endogenous
CC   retrovirus. There are several copies of ATHILA6B_I in the genome;
CC   they are ~99% identical to the consensus sequence. The consensus
CC   sequence was derived from 3 proviral copies. These copies are
CC   flanked by 99% identical LTRs (ATHILA6A_LTR). They have generated
CC   5-bp target site duplications upon their integration into the
CC   genome.
CC   ATHILA6B_I encodes 1888-aa polyprotein, ATHILA6Bp (positions
CC   173-5815). A middle portion of ATHILA6Bp is composed of the
CC   reverse transcriptase and integrase domains. These domains are
CC   encoded by a DNA region, which starts and ends at positions 3170
CC   and
CC   5683, respectively.
CC   ATHILA6B_I and ATHILA6A_I share identical ~1400-bp and ~1850-bp
CC   3'- and 5' ends, respectively. However, their central portions
CC   (positions 2475-6118 in ATHILA6B_I) are not similar to each
CC   other.
CC   Since, the central portion of ATHILA6B_I encodes the reverse
CC   transcriptase and integrase, ATHILA6A was a non-autonomous
CC   retroelement, whose transposition was mediated by ATHILA6B.
XX

RN   [1]
RP   1-4754
RA   Kapitonov V.V. and Jurka J.;
RT   "The ATHILA7A subfamily.";
RL   Repbase Reports 1(4), 8-8 (2001).
XX
DR   GenBank; AC005965; Positions   72809   68056.
XX
CC   ATHILA7A_I is an internal portion of ATHILA7A endogenous
CC   retrovirus.
CC   It belongs to the Gypsy superfamily and is related to the
CC   ATHILA-like
CC   endogenous retroviruses. ATHILA7A is a subfamily of the ATHILA7
CC   family. ATHILA7A_I and ATHILA7_I share ~95% identical 1.6 kb 5'-
CC   and
CC   ~2 kb 3'-terminal portions.
CC   There are two well preserved copies of ATHILA7A_I present
CC   in the A. thaliana genome; they are 96% identical to each other
CC   and
CC   are flanked by the 2% divergent ATHILA7LTR long terminal repeats.
CC   ATHILA7A_I encodes well preserved remnants of a protein similar
CC   to
CC   the ATHILA ORF1 protein (it is present also in other ATHILA-like
CC   retroviruses that populate the O. sativa, H. vulgare and V. faba
CC   genomes). The protein, ATHILA7Ap, is 930-aa. One false stop codon
CC   present in the copy deposited in Repbase Update is corrected
CC   based
CC   on the second ATHILA7A copy and other ATHILA ORF1-like proteins
CC   deposited in GenBank.
XX

DE   - a fossil.

XX
OS   Arabidopsis thaliana
OC   Eukaryota; Viridiplantae; Streptophyta; Embryophyta; Tracheophyta;
OC   Spermatophyta; Magnoliophyta; eudicotyledons; Gunneridae;

XX
RN   [1]
RP   1-9988
RA   Kapitonov V.V. and Jurka J.;
RT   "The ATHILA7 family.";
RL   Repbase Reports 1(4), 10-10 (2001).
XX
DR   GenBank; AF272705; Positions   12598    2611.
XX
CC   ATHILA7_I is an internal portion of ATHILA7 endogenous
CC   retrovirus.
CC   It belongs to the Gypsy superfamily and is related to the
CC   ATHILA-like
CC   endogenous retroviruses. ATHILA7_I is flanked by 7% divergent
CC   ATHILA7LTR long terminal repeats. Therefore this element has
CC   been inserted in the genome relatively long time ago; the same
CC   is confirmed by multiple stop codons disrupting three ORFs, which
CC   encode remnants of the ATHILA ORF1-like protein, reverse
CC   transcriptase and a hypothetical protein, correspondingly.
CC   Interestingly, there is one proviral copy of a very young
CC   retrovirus (AB005248, positions 24125-35848) that has LTRs and
CC   internal portion 91% and 93% identical to ATHILA7LTR and
CC   ATHILA7_I,
CC   correspondingly. This element is flanked by 100% identical LTRs,
CC   and
CC   its internal portion is not saturated by as many false stop
CC   codons as
CC   it happened in ATHILA7.
XX

CC   endogenous
CC   retrovirus. There are ~20 copies of ATHILA8ALTR in the genome;

CC   duplications.

DR   [1] (Consensus)
XX
CC   ATHILA8A_I is an internal portion of the nonautonomous ATHILA8A
CC   endogenous retrovirus. There are ~10 copies of ATHILA8A_I in the
CC   genome;
CC   they are ~91% identical to the consensus sequence. The consensus
CC   sequence was derived from 9 proviral copies. The internal portion
CC   is flanked by ~90% identical LTRs (ATHILA8ALTR). Given the
CC   divergence of the flanking LTRs, ATHILA8A is older than ATHILA1-7
CC   retrotransposons.
CC   Second half of ATHILA8A_I (positions 2600-5635) is ~60% identical
CC   to the internal portions of ATHILA4, ATHILA4A and ATHILA4C,
CC   including part of the Athila-like ORF1.
CC   The first half of ATHILA8A_I encodes a protein, ATHILA8A1p,
CC   which is not similar to any retroviral proteins or proteins
CC   encoded by other ATHILA-like elements.
CC   ATHILA8p1
CC   MNSRNYPNSYYPNVNHGSNRGSHFSTGHYTPDASQMHGESWQSWSSNGGAYRTDHYSNDQSATFVQNRPQ
CC   ANRSVSPFHHCVPSPRDQRVGGPHSSHPYGVARHEDFGYDQGYLQEVMSVDVHPNNYAYQTNEPYQTAEL
CC   EDKLIGLLQDFVDDHQEDVKRIDSKMTEMKAKFEEKFDDLTNRLENMEGALVEINNTLLNHQDDIQDQNT
CC   RIVNVGFAVDTVESHLDWKIEELEKKLTNSNEFSEWRSNQSCQEEDEFPKAQARYEEETKKEIGFLVEKG
CC   KDLISYSEKGNLDPIKSLGISIPFVSPQDQIEQEEDLEEEEAVSFEEDSMAEHNSREESLETEKEEVCLE
CC   SQENRFEELSEESDELTNFSSEEGEDEELKDVHSCMAIRLPSGGIPANPSFGQLGSLEEANPRGSLGAIQ
CC   ANRPFHVGEDLDAARRAQPSRFRTPYPRRAEESYPAQHYRPPVLPMLSTRDRSHMPWKHKTHEERLEILV
CC   SQFLDQQALDTRKLNARIDDIEVTLLSKVDALFVKFKKSEGSRVKEAEANEERFKKIEEEQERHLKSAQD
CC   NAINTRALLRQISNSDKDYDAKIEALSDKDANLVSRLGKLEDHLYEEQRRVDDLSYQQNRFHETLSERTI
CC   LAAGNDELDPRDKREWSPCSGKDFSSISQDDLRRIQSRMEGVDESIWRLQTRINQLEDNDAKEDVALEDV
CC   IRRQGEVEENQVKNVDDQSKIRASLRRVTMESSRKYVELLDRILDLDKKVDNLSTRIEGHEPMESEEEDS

CC   ATHILA8A is most closely related to ATHILA8B which encoded
CC   a complete ORF1-like protein, instead of ATHILA8A1p in ATHILA8A.

CC   ATHILA8BLTR is a long terminal repeat from the ATHILA8B
CC   endogenous
CC   retrovirus. There are ~10 copies of ATHILA8BLTR in the genome;
CC   they are ~95% identical to the consensus sequence.
CC   Solo LTRs and proviral copies are flanked by 5-bp target-site
CC   duplications. There is a 78% identity between the ATHILA8BLTR and
CC   ATHILA8ALTR consensus sequences.
CC   See comments for ATHILA8B_I.

CC   ATHILA8B_I is an internal portion of the ATHILA8B
CC   endogenous retrovirus. There are several copies of ATHILA8B_I
CC   in the genome; they are ~90% identical to the consensus sequence.
CC   The consensus sequence was derived from 4 proviral copies.
CC   The internal portion
CC   is flanked by 90-92% identical LTRs (ATHILA8BLTR).
CC   Second half of ATHILA8B_I (positions 2707-5020) is 85% identical
CC   to the second half of the ATHILA8A_I internal portion
CC   (see comments for ATHILA8A_I).
CC   The first half of ATHILA8B_I (positions 483-2696) encodes a
CC   737-aa
CC   protein, ATHILA8B1p, which is similar to the ATHILA ORF1-like
CC   proteins.

CC   ATHILA_I is an internal portion of the ATHILA LTR
CC   retrotransposon.
CC   ATHILA 10.5 kb elements, representing 0.3% of the genome, present
CC   several features of retrotransposons and retroviruses. Athila
CC   elements
CC   are flanked by 1.5 kb long terminal repeats (ATHILA_LTR) that are
CC   themselves bounded by 5 bp perfect inverted repeats. These LTRs
CC   start and end with the retroviral consensus 5'TG...CA3'
CC   nucleotides.
CC   A tRNA-binding site and a polypurine tract are found adjacent to
CC   the 5'
CC   and 3' LTR respectively. The central domain is composed of two
CC   long
CC   open reading frames (ORFs) of 935 and 694 amino acids. Despite
CC   several
CC   indications of recent transposition activity, the translation of
CC   these
CC   ORFs failed to reveal significant homology with proteins
CC   associated to
CC   retrotransposition. The authors suggest that the Athila family
CC   could
CC   result from the transduction and dispersion of a cellular gene by
CC   a
CC   retrotransposon.
CC   primer_bind 4..18
CC   /note="complementary to Lupine tRNAglu 3' end"
CC   CDS 193..3000
CC   /note="Athila ORF 1"
CC   /codon_start=1
CC   mRNA 3709..>5793
CC   /note="Athila ORF 2"
CC   misc_feature 7407..7413
CC   /note="poly purine track".

CC   ATHPOGO is a pogo-like autonomous DNA transposon.
CC   It is flanked by TA target-site duplicates.
CC   This transposon has 24 bp-long terminal inverted repeats;
CC   its ORF encodes pogo-like transposase.
CC   Current release of GenBank representing about 50% of
CC   the A.thaliana genome contains only one copy of ATHPOGO element
CC   which encodes transposase.
CC   Nonautonomous forms of ATHPOGO are deposited in Repbase as
CC   ATHPOGON1 and ATHPOGON2 families.
XX

DR   [1] (Consensus)
XX
CC   ATHPOGON1 is a pogo-like nonautonomous DNA transposon.
CC   Its individual copies are 90% identical to the consensus
CC   sequence. They are flanked by TA target-site duplicates.
CC   This transposon has 24 bp-long terminal inverted repeats;
CC   the remaining central portion is AT-reach. There are about
CC   150 copies of ATHPOGON1 in the haploid A.thaliana genome.
CC   Transposase involved in mobility of ATHPOGON1 elements
CC   is encoded by ATHPOGO autonomous transposon.

RN   [2]

RA   Kapitonov V.V. and Jurka J.;
RT   "ATIS112A is an autonomous DNA transposon.";
RL   Repbase Reports 3(10), 182-182 (2003).
XX
DR   [2] (Consensus)
XX
CC   ATIS112A is an autonomous DNA transposon.
CC   There are several copies of the transposon in the A.thaliana
CC   genome which are more than 90% identical to each other.
CC   They are bordered by 3 bp-long target site duplications.
CC   ATIS112A has 25 bp-long terminal inverted repeat.
CC   ATIS112A encodes two proteins, ATIS112A-1p and ATIS112A-2p.
CC   The 320-aa ATIS112A-1p is a putative DNA binding protein that
CC   includes the SANT/myb/trihelix motif. The protein is encoded by
CC   3 exons (834-922, 1262-1444 and 1498-2188).
CC   ATIS112A-2p is a 484-aa Harbinger-like DNA transposase, which is
CC   related to the transposase encoded by the bacterial IS112/IS5
CC   transposons (pos. 3583-5034).
CC   There are several other highly divergent families of Harbingers
CC   present in the A. thaliana genome [1].
CC   Originally, the transposon was described by [1]. The consensus
CC   sequence derived by [2] encodes the complete transposase.
XX

CC   retrovirus. There are about 10 copies of ATLANTYS1_I in the
CC   genome;
CC   they are ~97% identical to the consensus sequence. Long terminal
CC   repeats from ATLANTYS1 are deposited in Repbase Update as
CC   ATLANTYS1_LTR. ATLANTYS1 has generated 5-bp target site
CC   duplications.
CC   ATLANTYS1_I encodes a 2030aa polyprotein, ATLANTYS1p1, composed
CC   of gag, reverse transcriptase, RNase H and integrase domains:
CC   ATLANTYS1p1 (exons 75-5635 and 5676, predicted by GENSCAN).
CC   The second strand encodes 824-aa protein, ATLANTYS1p2, similar
CC   distantly to ORF3 in the the rice RIRE2 retrovirus. Its
CC   C-terminal
CC   portion (position 600-800) is related to a coiled coil
CC   domain present in the myosin heavy chain.
CC   ATLANTYS1p2 is encoded by 8 exons (10596-10576, 10483-10337,
CC   10096-9842, 9676-9385, 9271-9035, 8928-8204, 8130-7981,
CC   7906-7259;
CC   predicted by GENSCAN).
CC   ATLANTYS1 forms a distinctive superfamily of GYPSY-like
CC   retroviruses
CC   together with RIRE2 and RETROSOR1 found in the oryza sativa and
CC   the sorghum bicolor genomes. These retroviruses have ~10 kb
CC   internal
CC   sequences and their second strands encode a structural-like
CC   protein with a coiled coil domain.
XX

CC   ATLANTYS1_LTR is a consensus sequence of a long terminal repeat
CC   from the ATLANTYS1 endogenous retrovirus. An internal portion
CC   of the retrovirus is deposited in Repbase Update as ATLANTYS1_I.
CC   There are about 40 copies of ATLANTYS1_LTR in the genome, they
CC   are 97% identical to the consensus sequence. There is only 3.5%
CC   average divergence between ATLANTYS1_LTR copies which flank the
CC   same
CC   internal sequence.

CC   ATLANTYS2_I is an internal portion of the ATLANTYS2 endogenous
CC   retrovirus. There are several copies of ATLANTYS2_I in the
CC   genome;
CC   they are ~97% identical to the consensus sequence. Long terminal
CC   repeats from ATLANTYS2 are deposited in Repbase Update as
CC   ATLANTYS2_LTR. ATLANTYS2 has generated 5-bp target site
CC   duplications.
CC   ATLANTYS2_I encodes a 1867-aa polyprotein, ATLANTYS2p1, composed
CC   of gag, protease, reverse transcriptase, RNase H and integrase
CC   domains.
CC   ATLANTYS2p1 (CDS 73-2388 and 2476-5763, predicted by FGENESH):

DR   [1] (Consensus)
XX
CC   ATLANTYS2_LTR is a consensus sequence of a long terminal repeat
CC   from the ATLANTYS2 endogenous retrovirus. An internal portion
CC   of the retrovirus is deposited in Repbase Update as ATLANTYS2_I.
CC   There are about 10 copies of ATLANTYS2_LTR in the genome, they
CC   are ~97% identical to the consensus sequence. There is only 3%
CC   average divergence between ATLANTYS2_LTR copies which flank the
CC   same internal sequence.

CC   ATLANTYS3I is an internal portion of the ATLANTYS3 endogenous
CC   retrovirus. There are several copies of ATLANTYS3I in the genome;
CC   they are over 90% identical to each other. Long terminal
CC   repeats are deposited in Repbase Update as ATLANTYS3LTR
CC   ATLANTYS3I is flanked by 98% identical LTRs and has 5-bp TSD.
CC   Like other members of the ATLANTYS superfamily, ATLANTYS3I
CC   encodes s hypothetical protein in reverse orientation, instead
CC   of env.

XX
CC   ATLINE1_1 is a non-LTR retrotransposon. Its individual copies are
CC   99% identical to each other. There are only a few copies of
CC   ATLINE1_1 present in the genome. ATLINE1_1 belongs to the L1
CC   superfamily of non-LTR retrotransposons, its copies are flanked
CC   by ~15-bp target site duplications.
CC   Two proteins, ATLINE1_1p1 and ATLINE1_1p2, are encoded by ORF1
CC   (position 17-1609) and ORF2 (position 1652-5782) respectively.
CC   Function and classification of the first protein is unclear,
CC   although
CC   it is expected to be a nucleic acid binding protein analogously
CC   to
CC   the protein encoded by L1 in mammals. The second protein contains
CC   the reverse transcriptase and endonuclease domains.
CC   ATLINE1_1p1 (530 aa):

CC   ATLINE1_2 is a non-LTR retrotransposon. Its individual copies are
CC   98% identical to each other. There are only a few copies of
CC   ATLINE1_2 present in the genome. ATLINE1_2 belongs to the L1
CC   superfamily of non-LTR retrotransposons, its copies are flanked
CC   by ~15-bp target site duplications.
CC   Two proteins, ATLINE1_2p1 and ATLINE1_2p2, are encoded by ORF1
CC   (position 2-1579) and ORF2 (position 1622-5752), respectively.
CC   Function and classification of the first protein is unclear,
CC   although
CC   it is expected to be a nucleic acid binding protein analogously
CC   to
CC   the protein encoded by L1 in mammals. The second protein contains
CC   the reverse transcriptase and endonuclease domains.
CC   ATLINE1_2p1 (525 aa):

CC   ATLINE1_4 is a non-LTR retrotransposon. Its individual copies are
CC   ~88% identical to each other. There are only 3 copies of
CC   ATLINE1_4 present in the genome. ATLINE1_4 belongs to the L1
CC   superfamily of non-LTR retrotransposons, its copies are flanked
CC   by ~15-bp target site duplications.
CC   Two proteins, ATLINE1_4p1 and ATLINE1_4p2, are encoded by ORF1
CC   (position 389-2380) and ORF2 (position 2551-6609), respectively.
CC   ATLINE1_4p2 contains the reverse transcriptase and endonuclease
CC   domains.

CC   ATLINE1_5 is a non-LTR retrotransposon. Its individual copies are
CC   ~88% identical to each other. There are only 3 copies of
CC   ATLINE1_5 present in the genome. ATLINE1_5 belongs to the L1
CC   superfamily of non-LTR retrotransposons, its copies are flanked
CC   by ~15-bp target site duplications.
CC   Two proteins, ATLINE1_5p1 and ATLINE1_5p2, are encoded by ORF1
CC   (position 431-2546) and ORF2 (position 2691-6710), respectively.
CC   Both ORFs are saturated by several false stop codons.
CC   Stop codons at positions 1019 and 5675 are replaced by R in the
CC   corresponding protein sequences, based on their comparison with
CC   other homologous proteins.

CC   ATLINE1_6 belongs to the L1 superfamily of non-LTR
CC   retrotransposons.
CC   It is a one-copy family; there are no other genomic retroelements
CC   that are more than 75% identical to ATLINE1_6.
CC   ATLINE1_6 has been inserted in the A. thaliana genome relatively
CC   recently, a few millions of years ago. It is flanked by a perfect
CC   15-bp TSD.
CC   Two proteins, ATLINE1_6p1 and ATLINE1_6p2, are encoded by ORF1
CC   (position 604-1416) and ORF2 (position 1537-5480, conceptual
CC   translation), respectively.
CC   Presumably ORF1 is incomplete because of a ~1-kb deletion that
CC   has happened after insertion of the retrotransposon in the
CC   genome.
CC   ORF2 is saturated by 4 false stop codons and one short indel;
CC   they
CC   are marked by X in the next protein sequences.
CC   ATLINE1_6p2 contains the reverse transcriptase and endonuclease
CC   domains.
XX

RT   thaliana.";
RL   Genetica 107(1-3), 27-37 (1999).
XX
DR   [1] (Consensus)
XX
CC   ATLINEIII is a non-LTR retrotransposon. Its individual copies are
CC   98% identical to the consensus sequence. There are several
CC   families
CC   of LINEs in the A.thaliana genomes distantly related to ATLINEIII
CC   (mutual identity is lower than 70%). The estimated number of
CC   ATLINEIII
CC   copies per haploid genome is about 10. Putatively, ATLINEIII has
CC   polIII-like internal promoter used by tRNA-Lys since 56 bp-long
CC   ATLINEIII 5'-terminus is 98% identical with tRNA-Lys.
CC   Two proteins are encoded by ORF1 (position 163-1623) and ORF2
CC   (position 1623-5168). Function and classification of the first
CC   protein is unclear; the second protein has conservative reverse
CC   transcriptase domain.
XX

DR   GenBank; AF077407; Positions   93315   98243.
XX
CC   ATMU1 is an autonomous DNA transposon from MUDR superfamily.
CC   It has 10 bp-long target site duplications and
CC   280 bp-long TIRs. These TIRs form several subfamilies of
CC   ATMU nonautonomous transposons. Transposase encoded by ATMU1
CC   is most close to the transposase encoded by ATMU2 transposon
CC   in the A.thaliana genome and MUDR transposons found in the maize
CC   genome. ATMU1 transposase has been identified before (see GenBank
CC   Accession No. AF077407).

OC   Camelineae; Arabidopsis.

RN   [1]
RP   1-4703
RA   Kapitonov V.V. and Jurka J.;
RT   "The ATMU10 family of MuDR-like transposons.";
RL   Repbase Reports 1(4), 16-16 (2001).
XX
DR   GenBank; AC006528; Positions   30888   35590.
XX
CC   ATMU10 is a fossil of an autonomous DNA transposon from the MuDR
CC   superfamily.
CC   ATMU10 is flanked by 95% identical 340-bp TIRs, and by 10-bp TSD.
CC   ATMU10 represents one of tens MuDR-like families present
CC   today in the A. thaliana genome.
CC   Exons that encode the ATMU10 transposase (~ positions 1000-3000)
CC   and putative DNA-binding proteins (~ positions 4350-3800) are
CC   damaged by a few mutations accumulated in the ATMU10 copy since
CC   its insertion into the genome.
XX

RA   Kapitonov V.V. and Jurka J.;
RT   "The ATMU11 family of MuDR-like transposons.";
RL   Repbase Reports 1(4), 17-17 (2001).
XX
DR   GenBank; AC021666; Positions   53477   57307.
XX
CC   ATMU11 is a fossil of an autonomous DNA transposon from the MuDR
CC   superfamily.
CC   ATMU11 is flanked by 90% identical ~240-bp TIRs.
CC   ATMU11 represents one of tens MuDR-like families present
CC   today in the A. thaliana genome.
CC   It is flanked by a 10-bp target site duplication.
CC   ATMU11 has preserved well the MuDr-like ATMU11p transposase.
CC   Presumably it was encoded originally by 4 exons. Exon 3 is
CC   currently damaged by a false stop codon at position 1848-1850.
CC   The stop codon is masked by X in the 743-aa ATMU11p protein
CC   sequence.
CC   CDS join (371..1237,1363..1590,1674..2648,2728..2889).
XX

XX
CC   ATMU2 is an autonomous DNA transposon from MUDR superfamily.
CC   It has 10 bp-long target site duplications and 290 bp-long TIRs.
CC   There is 78% identity between nucleotide sequences of ATMU2
CC   and ATMU1 transposons. Transposase encoded by ATMU2 is
CC   most close to the transposase encoded by ATMU1 transposon in
CC   A.thaliana and MUDR transposons found in the maize genome.
CC   ATMU2 transposase has been identified before (see GenBank
CC   Accession No. AC002130).

RN   [1]

RA   Kapitonov V.V. and Jurka J.;
RT   "ATMU3.";
RL   Direct Submission to Repbase Update (SEP-2000).
XX
DR   [1] (Consensus)
XX
CC   ATMU3 is an autonomous DNA transposon from MUDR superfamily.
CC   Its copies are flanked by 10-bp target site duplications.
CC   There are 5-10 copies of ATMU3 in the genome, they are ~99%
CC   identical to the consensus sequence. The consensus sequence
CC   was reconstructed based on 4 copies; therefore, it may
CC   represent well enough features of the active ATMU3 transposon.
CC   ATMU3 has ~280-bp terminal inverted repeats and encodes
CC   two proteins, ATMU3p1 and ATMU3p2.
CC   ATMU3p2 includes a conservative motif (aa positions 37-80)
CC   CKCGLEVVMFTSSTAKNPGRPFFRCKSCEDLEMELQDHLFKWVE present at
CC   C-terminus
CC   of DNA topoisomerase III in human, mouse and drosophila, and
CC   at C-terminus of polyproteins encoded by ORF3 in banana streak
CC   and sugarcane bacilliform retroid viruses.
CC   There are ~100 highly diverged copies of ATMU3p2 encoded by
CC   different families of ATMU-like DNA transposons and inserted
CC   in the genome.
XX
FH   Key           Location/Qualifiers

FT                 /note="putative DNA-binding protein"

FT                 DALPKISSIDNEIINAKAEVAVEIANLKELMIELKEDGMWSKREIQRWKKM
FT                 TKVCLCDCNCNINVL*"

DR   [1] (Consensus)
XX
CC   ATMU3N1 is a nonautonomous DNA transposon from MUDR superfamily.
CC   Its copies are flanked by 10-bp target site duplications.
CC   There are ~10 copies of ATMU3N1 in the genome, they are ~97%
CC   identical to the consensus sequence. The ATMU3N1 consensus
CC   sequence forms an imperfect palindrome and it has nearly
CC   identical
CC   126-bp terminal inverted repeats. There is an 85% identity
CC   between
CC   ~200-bp termini of ATMU3N1 and ATMU3.
XX

XX
KW   MuDR; DNA transposon; Transposable Element; ATMU4;
KW   DNA-binding protein; MUDR superfamily; TIR;
KW   Autonomous DNA transposon; transposase.
