XX
OS   Arabidopsis thaliana
OC   Eukaryota; Viridiplantae; Streptophyta; Embryophyta; Tracheophyta;
OC   Spermatophyta; Magnoliophyta; eudicotyledons; Gunneridae;
OC   Pentapetalae; rosids; malvids; Brassicales; Brassicaceae;
OC   Camelineae; Arabidopsis.
XX
RN   [1]
RP   1-4496
RA   Kapitonov V.V. and Jurka J.;
RT   "ATMU4.";
RL   Direct Submission to Repbase Update (SEP-2000).
XX
DR   GenBank; AC025417; Positions   80238   84733.
XX
CC   ATMU4 is a fossilized copy of autonomous DNA transposon from
CC   MUDR superfamily.
CC   It is flanked by a 10-bp target site duplication.
CC   ATMU4 has 280-bp terminal inverted repeats and encodes
CC   two proteins, ATMU4p1 and ATMU4p2.
CC   ATMU4p2 includes a conservative motif (aa positions 26-63)
CC   CHCGLEVVIYTSASKSNPGRPFFRCPTKQDDHLFKWVE present at C-terminus
CC   of DNA topoisomerase III in human, mouse and drosophila, and
CC   at C-terminus of polyproteins encoded by ORF3 in banana streak
CC   and sugarcane bacilliform retroid viruses.
CC   There are ~100 highly diverged copies of ATMU4p2 encoded by
CC   different families of ATMU-like DNA transposons and inserted
CC   in the genome.
XX

CC   ATMU5 is a fossilized copy of autonomous DNA transposon from
CC   MUDR superfamily.
CC   It is flanked by a 10-bp target site duplication.
CC   ATMU5 has ~310-bp terminal inverted repeats (94% identity) and
CC   encodes two proteins, ATMU5p1 and ATMU5p2.
CC   Conservation of the proteins and TIRs indicates that
CC   the transposon was active recently. One copy of non-autonomous
CC   derivative of ATMU5 is present in the genome (AC079674 25687-
CC   25111). The non-autonomous element is 95% identical to ATMU5
CC   and is a result of a deletion of the ATMU5 internal portion.
CC   ATMU5 is 74% identical with ATMU3 and ATMU4.
CC   ATMU5p1 is a 684-aa transposase encoded by 4 exons (359-1486,
CC   1588-1839, 1926-2591, 2657-2665).
CC   ATMU5p1:
CC   MGGVISTIGSGESESVVDRGVEVAVELESVVGDGVEVPPVEAPVGIELVARGEDCVPSRH
CC   RKRRKIRVGDEDEAEIDPDPDYEDDCAVHGDEDCDAYTDAVGGDDDATGGEGNDDEAVGG
CC   GDDATGCGGNDDEALGYDDDATSDGGNDDDDGGVEEDANLNLAEEFPEFAGVEEDCSDDD
CC   PPDDVWEEDKIPDPFSSDDEDESRTREVHGHRDAANEEVLLELKKTYNTPDDFKLAVLRY
CC   SLKTRYDIKLFRSEARIVAAKCSYVDKDGVQCPWKVYCSYEKTMHKMQIRTYVNNHICVR
CC   SGHSKMLKRSSIAYLFEERLRVNPKLTKYEMAAEILREYNLEVTPDQCAKAKTKVVKARN
CC   ASHEAHFARVWDYQAEAQKDSWIKTCRPFIGLDGAFLKWDIKGHLLAAVGRDGDNKIVPI
CC   AWAVVEIENDDNWDWFLRHLSASLGLCQMANIAILSDKQSGLVKAIHTILPHAEHRQCSK
CC   HIMDNWKRDSHDLELQRLFWKIARSYTVEEFNNHMMELQQYNRQAYESLQLTSPVTWSRA
CC   FFRIGTCCNDNLNNLSESFNRTIRQARRKPILDMLEDIRRQCMVRSAKRFLIAEKLQTRF
CC   TKRAHEEIEKMIVGLRQCERYMARENLHEIYVNNVSYFVDMEQKTCDCRKCQMVGIPCIH
CC   ATCVIIGKKEKVEDYVSDYYTKDE
CC   ATMU5p2 is a putative 258-aa DNA-binding protein, it is
CC   encoded by 3 exons in the second strand (4513-4361, 4294-4211,
CC   3488-2949).
CC   ATMU5p2:
CC   MSLEISSVGEEGSGNRGFPSKCRCGRDVVIYTSSSKKNPGRPYFRCPTYQDDHLFKWVED
CC   CVYEEVVDAIPRISIIDSEVAVLVMVHLLVFVLHDHHLMLFVLVLHNHDLQPFVLVLRDH
CC   DLQPLVLVLRDHDLQHLVLVLRDHDLQHLVLVIQDHDLQHLVLVIQDHDLQHLVLVIQDH
CC   DLQHLVLVIQDHDLQHLVLVIQDQPVILDEIVVALVIQDKIVIALVIQDKIEIQTLLVLK
CC   LKKRVRNTCWIVKKESHK
CC   ATMU5p2 includes a conservative motif (aa positions 26-63)
CC   CHCGLEVVIYTSASKSNPGRPFFRCPTKQDDHLFKWVE present at C-terminus
CC   of DNA topoisomerase III in human, mouse and drosophila, and
CC   at C-terminus of polyproteins encoded by ORF3 in banana streak
CC   and sugarcane bacilliform retroid viruses.

CC   ATMU6 is a fossilized copy of autonomous DNA transposon from
CC   MUDR superfamily.
CC   It is flanked by a 10-bp target site duplication.
CC   ATMU6 has 210-bp terminal inverted repeats and encodes
CC   two proteins, ATMU6p1 and ATMU6p2, similar to these
CC   encoded by ATMU5, ATMU4 and ATMU3.
CC   Regions coding for ATMU6p1 and ATMU6p2 are saturated by multiple
CC   false stop codons and deletions, the ATMU6 TIRs are 77%
CC   identical.
CC   ATMU6 is older than its closest relatives ATMU5, ATMU4 and ATMU3.
CC   ATMU6 is 76% identical with ATMU5 (72% identity with ATMU3 and
CC   ATMU4).

DR   [1] (Consensus)
XX
CC   ATMU6N1 is a non-autonomous DNA transposon from MUDR superfamily.
CC   Its copies are flanked by 10-bp target site duplications.
CC   There are 3 copies of ATMU6N1 in the genome, they are 97%
CC   identical to the consensus sequence. The ATMU6N1 consensus
CC   sequence forms an imperfect palindrome and it has 91% identical
CC   284-bp terminal inverted repeats. There is a 79% identity between
CC   ~220-bp termini of ATMU6N1 and ATMU6.
CC   ATMU6N1 (positions 278-657) harbors a portion of a host gene,
CC   which
CC   encodes the homeobox-leucine zipper protein Athb-1.
CC   Its exons1-2 and intron1 have been intercepted by the transposon.

CC   ATMU7 is an autonomous DNA transposon from MUDR superfamily.
CC   Its copies are flanked by 10-bp target site duplications.
CC   There are 2 copies of ATMU7 in the genome, they are 98%
CC   identical to each other. ATMU7 was active recently.
CC   However, both copies have lost some portions of the
CC   transposase and DNA-binding protein.
CC   ATMU7 has ~320-bp terminal inverted repeats, 92% identical
CC   with each other. ATMU7 encodes two proteins, ATMU7p1 and
CC   ATMU7p2.
CC   ATMU7p1 is a truncated 357-aa transposase encoded by 3 exons
CC   (358-843, 899-1267 and 1530-1748).
CC   ATMU7p1:
CC   MRKKLPADVDPPPPVVEPPHVVVEPPSASIEPPSASIEPPSVAIEPPSVAELRRASVEAP
CC   AIHEPSTRPSHSVVDNRRRKKSKQNGNRLDGDNRRKKSKSKQNGNESDGEGLSENDCNVT
CC   GDDDFDEVHYADEEDGNRLGVTEENCEDFEAHSGPAARDDGDGLVKAIHNRIPAAEHRQC
CC   AKHIMDNWKRNSHDMELQRLFWKIARSYTIGEYTANLEELKTYNPGAAASLMNTKPMEWS
CC   RAFFRIGSCCNDNLNNLSESFNRTIRQARRKPLLDMLEDIRSQCMKVEDYVSDWYTTRMW
CC   QLTYNDGIAPVQGQLLWPRVNRLGVLPPPWRRGTPGRPSNYARRKGRRSWFECSNLT
CC   ATMU7p2 is a truncated 143-aa DNA-binding protein encoded by
CC   the second strand (exons 2786-2575 and 2482-2264):
CC   XLKSISKIGSSYAMSSSSASSGVVQNRGFPVKCWCGDDVTIFTSKSVDNPGRPFFRCETK
CC   RDPKTWTNKRDSHLFKWVEDAVYEEVEDVLPKFVIIANELNKAKSEANELNVMIHELKEE
CC   AMLSKQEICKWKVCLKICFFGFV
CC   ATMU7 is only ~65% identical with ATMU3-ATMU6.
CC   The ATMU7 segment (2107-2750) that encodes ATMU7p2 is most
CC   close (81% identity) to the one present in VANDAL7 (6516-7144).

CC   ATMU8 is an autonomous DNA transposon from the MUDR superfamily.
CC   There is only one copy of ATMU8 in the genome.
CC   It is flanked by a 10-bp target site duplication.
CC   ATMU8 is 77 and 74% identical with ATMU5 and ATMU4 respectively.

CC   identical
CC   with each other. ATMU8 encodes two proteins, ATMU8p1 and ATMU8p2.

CC   ATMU9 is a fossil of a relatively ancient autonomous DNA
CC   transposon
CC   that belongs to the MuDR superfamily.
CC   There are only two copies of ATMU9 in the genome (chromosomes 2
CC   and 3; they are 87% identical to each other.
CC   ATMU9 is flanked by 90% identical ~240-bp TIRs.
CC   ATMU9 represents one of tens MuDR-like families present
CC   today in the A. thaliana genome.
CC   It is flanked by a 10-bp target site duplication.
CC   Exons that encode the ATMU9 transposase (~ positions 780-3600)
CC   are
CC   damaged by several mutations accumulated in the ATMU9 copy since
CC   its insertion into the genome. A short ~150-aa protein is encoded
CC   by the second strand (positions 4350-3819). The protein is
CC   conserved
CC   in different ATMU families; we classify it as a DNA-binding
CC   protein.
XX

DR   [1] (Consensus)
XX
CC   ATN9_1 is a putative nonautonomous DNA transposon that may be
CC   mobile currently.
CC   Its individual copies are 98% identical to the consensus
CC   sequence. They are flanked by 9 bp-long target-site duplicates.
CC   This element does not have terminal inverted repeats. However,
CC   we consider ATN9_1 as a nonautonomous DNA transposon mobilized
CC   by MUDR-like transposase because MUDR-related transposons induce
CC   9 or 10 bp-long target-site duplications and are flanked by
CC   5'-GGG and 3'-CCC (ATMU - like elements) or do not have TIRs
CC   like ARNOLD/VNDAL-like transposons.
CC   There are about 50 copies of ATN9_1 in the haploid A.thaliana
CC   genome.
XX

CC   HELITRON-like
CC   transposons. There is <75% nucleotide identity between ATREP10C

CC   they have been inserted into AT target sites without duplications
CC   of the sites.

DR   [4] (Consensus)
XX
CC   Individual copies of ATREP3 are ~97% identical to the ATREP3
CC   consensus sequence. There are several minor ATREP3 subfamilies
CC   determined by multiple diagnostic positions in multiple
CC   alignment;
CC   multiple copies of ATREP3 have internal deletions typical for
CC   DNA transposons.
CC   ATREP3 shares common structural features with other ATREPn
CC   elements and HELITRONs; all these elements have conservative
CC   termini: 5'-TC and CTAG-3', and they have been inserted in the AT
CC   target sites, precisely between the 5'-A and T-3', without
CC   duplications or deletions of genomic DNA.

XX
DR   [1] (Consensus)
XX
CC   There are several dozens copies of the ATREPX1 repeat in the
CC   genome;
CC   they are ~91% identical to the consensus sequence.
CC   ATREPX1 shares common 5'-ATC and CTAGT-3' termini with repeats
CC   from ATREP superfamily.
CC   Presumably, both groups of repeats relay on the same mechanism of
CC   transposition.
CC   ATREPX1 is a composite transposons since it carries
CC   (position 276-753) an insertion of ATHATN1, a HAT-like DNA
CC   transposon.
XX

DR   [1] (Consensus)
XX
CC   ATSINE1's individual copies are ~80% identical to the consensus
CC   sequence. Poly(A) tail and ~15 bp-long target-site duplications
CC   indicate that ATSINE1 is a SINE-like retroelement.
CC   Common structure of the 3'-tail in ATLINE1_3A and ATSINE may
CC   indicate
CC   that ATSINE1 has been transposed because of the ATLINE1 activity.
CC   Renamed to AtSB4 for  consistency with more recent
CC   classifications (May 4, 2006).

DR   [2] (Consensus)
XX
CC   ATLINE1A is a putative non-autonomous transposon which belongs to
CC   the mariner/Tc1 superfamily [2] since it has TA target site and
CC   ~30 bp-long terminal inverted repeats.
CC   Individual copies are about 94% identical to the consensus
CC   sequence.

CC   ATTIRX1A is a subfamily of putative non-autonomous DNA
CC   transposons ATTIRX1.
CC   Its individual copies are ~87% identical to the consensus
CC   sequence. They are flanked by TAA target site duplications.
CC   This transposon has 16 bp-long terminal inverted repeats.

CC   transposons ATTIRX1.
CC   Its individual copies are ~86% identical to the consensus
CC   sequence.
CC   This transposon has 40 bp-long non-perfect TIRs.

CC   consensus sequences.

RT   "ATTIRX1C.";
RL   Direct Submission to Repbase Update (JAN-2000).
XX
DR   [1] (Consensus)
XX
CC   ATTIRX1C is a family of putative non-autonomous DNA
CC   transposons related to the ATTIRX1 group.
CC   Its individual copies are ~97% identical to the consensus
CC   sequence. They are flanked by TAA or TTA target site
CC   duplications.
CC   This transposon has 22 bp-long terminal inverted repeats.
CC   There are about several dozens of the ATTIRX1C copies scattered
CC   in the genome.
XX

DR   [1] (Consensus)
XX
CC   ATTIRX1D is a subfamily of putative non-autonomous DNA
CC   transposons ATTIRX1.
CC   Its individual copies are ~95% identical to the consensus
CC   sequence and they are flanked by duplications of the TTA
CC   target site. This transposon has 29-bp imperfect TIRs.
CC   There is 74% identity between the ATTIRX1D and ATTIRX1B
CC   consensus sequences.
XX

DR   [1] (Consensus)
XX
CC   BOMZH1 is a putative non-autonomous DNA transposon.
CC   Its individual copies are 98% identical to the consensus
CC   sequence. They are bordered by 10 bp-long target site
CC   duplications.
CC   This transposon is an imperfect palindrome. Its 13 bp-long TIRs
CC   are identical with BRODYAGA1 TIRs.

CC   BOMZH2 is a putative non-autonomous DNA transposon.
CC   Its individual copies are ~90% identical to the consensus
CC   sequence. They are bordered by 10 bp-long target site
CC   duplications.
CC   DNA sequence of BOMZH2 forms an imperfect palindrome.
CC   There are ~10 copies of BOMZH2 in the genome.

DR   [1] (Consensus)
XX
CC   BRODYAGA1 is a putative non-autonomous DNA transposon.
CC   Its individual copies are 98% identical to the consensus
CC   sequence. They are flanked by 10 bp-long target site duplicates.
CC   This transposon has ~350 bp-long terminal inverted repeats; the
CC   remaining central portion is AT-reach.

XX

RT   "HARBINGER.";
RL   Direct Submission to Repbase Update (06-MAY-1999).
XX
RN   [2]
RA   Kapitonov V.V. and Jurka J.;
RT   "Molecular paleontology of transposable elements from Arabidopsis
RT   thaliana.";
RL   Genetica 107(1-3), 27-37 (1999).
XX
DR   GenBank; AC005850; Positions   72305   77686.
XX
CC   HARBINGER is a putative autonomous DNA transposon.
CC   There are several copies of the transposon in the A.thaliana
CC   genome which are more than 90% identical to each other.
CC   They are bordered by 3 bp-long target site duplications.
CC   HARBINGER has 25 bp-long terminal inverted repeat.
CC   One of nonautonomous forms of HARBINGER was deposited recently
CC   in Repbase as SIMPLEGUY1. HARBINGER encodes two proteins:
CC   (1) position 1963-2400, its function is unknown; (2)
CC   DNA transposase, position 3282-4332.
CC   HARBINGER represents novel superfamily of DNA transposons.
CC   Transposons related to HARBINGER encode similar transposases
CC   and populate bacterial, plant and invertebrate (C.elegans)
CC   genomes.
XX

DR   [2] (Consensus)
XX
CC   HELITRON1 is a DNA transposon.
CC   It encodes a DNA helicase-like 1697-aa protein, ATHEL2p.
CC   HELITRON1 encodes also proteins ATRPA1H1p and ATRPA1H3p
CC   similar to the replication protein A.
CC   There are several copies of HELITRON1 in the
CC   genome; they are ~98% identical to the consensus sequence.
CC   Approximately 2% of the A. thaliana genome belongs to molecular
CC   fossils of non-autonomous elements transposed recently (<10 Myrs)
CC   by autonomous HELITRON1-like elements. ATREP1-ATREP12 are
CC   families
CC   of non-autonomous elements transposed by HELITRON1-like DNA
CC   transposons. All these elements share the same 5'-TC and
CC   CTAG-3' termini, the AT target site, and they do not generate
CC   duplications of the target sites upon insertion into the genome.
CC   There are several other families of HELITRON1-like transposons
CC   in the A.thaliana genome that are only 60-70% identical to the
CC   HELITRON1 consensus sequence.
XX

RL   Proc Natl Acad Sci USA 98(15), 8714-8719 (2001).

DR   [2] (Consensus)
XX
CC   HELITRON2 is a DNA transposon.
CC   There are 10-20 copies of HELITRON2 in the
CC   genome; they are ~95% identical to the consensus sequence.
CC   HELITRON2 transposes precisely in the AT target sites, without
CC   duplication of the host DNA.
CC   HELITRON2 carries two genes that encode proteins ATRPA2Hp and
CC   ATHEL2p, respectively.
CC   ATRPA2Hp is 518 aa long, is encoded by 10 exons (position
CC   1133-3605) and is similar to the large subunit of RPA1,
CC   the replication protein A.
CC   ATHEL2p is 1774 aa long and is encoded by 11 exons
CC   (position 4441-10829). It is composed of the rolling-circle
CC   replication initiator and DNA helicase domains.
XX

CC   HELITRON3 is a DNA transposon that belongs to the HELITRON
CC   superfamily. There are two copies of HELITRON3 in the
CC   genome; they are ~93% identical to each other.
CC   HELITRON3 encodes 3 proteins similar to the replication
CC   protein A: 404-aa ATRPA3H1p, 272-aa ATRPA3H2p and 201-aa
CC   ATRPA3H3p. It encodes also one 1190-aa protein ATHEL3p
CC   composed of the rolling-circle initiator and DNA helicase
CC   domains.
XX

DR   [2] (Consensus)
XX
CC   HELITRON4 is a DNA transposon that belongs to the HELITRON
CC   superfamily. It encodes an 1526-aa protein, ATHEL4p, composed
CC   of the rolling-circle and DNA helicase domains, and three
CC   RPA70-like proteins, ATRPA4H1p, ATRPA4H2p, and ATRPA4H3p.
CC   There are five copies of HELITRON4 in the genome;
CC   they are ~95% identical to the consensus sequence.

CC   HELITRON5 is a DNA transposon that belongs to the HELITRON
CC   superfamily. It encodes ATHEL5p, a 1752-aa DNA helicase-like
CC   protein,
CC   and ATRPA5p, a 475-aa protein similar to the replication protein
CC   A.
CC   HELITRON3 is inserted into the AT target site.

DR   [2] (Consensus)
XX
CC   HELITRONY1A is a non-autonomous DNA transposon.
CC   There are several copies of HELITRONY1A in the genome; they are
CC   ~94% identical to the consensus sequence.
CC   HELITRONY1A transposes precisely in the AT target sites, without
CC   duplication of the host DNA.
CC   There is 76% identity between HELITRONY1A and ATREP5 over their
CC   complete lengths (several long indels); they share ~90% identical
CC   30-bp 5' and 3' termini.
CC   There is 70% nucleotide identity between ~160-bp 5'-terminal
CC   portions of HELITRONY1A and HELITRON1; their 20-bp 5' termini
CC   are identical); their ~150-bp 3'-termini are 70% identical
CC   with each other.
XX

CC   HELITRONY1B is a non-autonomous DNA transposon.
CC   There are several copies of HELITRONY1B in the genome; they are
CC   ~94% identical to the consensus sequence.
CC   HELITRONY1B transposes precisely in the AT target sites, without
CC   duplication of the host DNA.
CC   There is 82% identity between HELITRONY1B and HELITRONY1A.
CC   There is 81% identity between HELITRONY1B (position 133-1313) and
CC   ATREP5 (188-2388); their 30-bp 3'- and 20-bp 5'-termini are
CC   90% and 95% identical with each other.
CC   HELITRONY1B and HELITRON1 share the 100% and 85% identical 20-bp
CC   5'-
CC   and 33-bp 3'-termini, respectively.

CC   HELITRONY1C is a non-autonomous DNA transposon related to an
CC   autonomous HELITRON1-like transposon.
CC   There are two 94% identical copies of HELITRONY1C in the genome.
CC   There is a 87% identity between HELITRONY1C (position 1-3060) and
CC   ATREP11 (1-1055); their 30-bp 3'- and 19-bp 5'-termini are
CC   90% and 100% identical with each other.
CC   HELITRONY1C and HELITRON1 share the 88% and 72% identical 230-bp
CC   5'- and 180-bp 3'-termini, respectively.
CC   There is a 68% identity between HELITRONY1C and HELITRONY1A
CC   (they share the 100% and 91% identical 20-bp 5' and 30-bp 3'
CC   termini, respectively).

DR   [2] (Consensus)
XX
CC   HELITRONY2 is a non-autonomous HELITRON-like DNA transposon.
CC   There are ~10 copies of HELITRONY2 in the genome; they are ~97%
CC   identical to the consensus sequence.
CC   HELITRONY2 transposes precisely in the AT target sites, without
CC   duplication of the host DNA.
CC   HELITRONY2 carries four genes that encode proteins ATRPA1HY1p,
CC   ATRPA1HY2p, ATRPA1HY3p and ATRPA1HY4p, respectively.
CC   ATRPA1HY1p is 518 aa long and is encoded by 10 exons (position
CC   1057-3521), it is similar to the large subunit of RPA1, the
CC   replication protein A:
CC   MMLANPLPFTPLKSLKPYKNAWRIQVKLLHVWRQYSVKAGESIEMILVDKAGDKMYAAVR
CC   REQIKKFERCLTEGVWKIITTITLNPTSGQYRISDLKYKIGFVFKTTVSPCDTVSDALFL
CC   SLAKFDVILSGSANSNILHDVMGQVVDRSEIQDLNANNKPTKKIDFHLRDQHDTRLACTL
CC   WGKYAEIVDKACQESTDGIVVCLIRFAKINLYNDTRSVSNSFDVSQVFVDPTLAELGLFK
CC   QSIPTDGLTLGSSGSFHKRLYAPRTGDDDGDYPRQTIKEVLTSSDVGKCKTVCTVSAIDT
CC   DWPWYYFCCRAHNKKVVKEEAIKLEDVKQPQKPRFWCEICNGFAKSVVAKFWLHLHIMDQ
CC   TGEARCMLFDSHAKEILGTTAPQLLDGSFDEIEDPTVLPDVINGLKGKTFQFLLCIQREN
CC   IFGGYDSFTVARVYTGNIVDEIVQEDSDAYVDPSSLISIEQGSLMLTNGVDLSDVDLSST
CC   STPSSKRKDSDDVDGNDQASTSRKKCSRMTMSEERSGE
CC   ATRPA1HY2p is 195 aa long and is encoded by 4 exons (position
CC   4254-4388), it is similar to the ssDNA-binding portion of the
CC   large subunit of RPA1:
CC   MSVHKLTDLRDNSTNWKINVKILSIWNHPPNSHGEITTMILHDDKNNRVDATIPQGNYHN
CC   PFRPFLKPGTWIHISDFRVVVPQSRVRYSSFRFHIKFIWETSVYPLPELVKRDFFDFIFP
CC   IDLKYPCLEDWDYVTDAMGVVTNISAIKKFLFVCRQGETDYESRYVSFELLDNIRGFEDY
CC   DELPKNPRMEVIEEN
CC   ATRPA1HY3p is 218 aa long and is encoded by 5 exons (position
CC   7087-8177), it is similar to the ssDNA-binding portion of the
CC   large subunit of RPA1:
CC   MIDAICAYFYTGYDVPRVLNEGGWFFLENILLIKSVGGRKPPLTDNKLRIKFLQTTKMTP
CC   VPNREPSNFFRFAAFSMIENKTINSSTVHDAYGIVVRVGNITRPDFVPQASENTILSQFL
CC   EFEIKNSCGYTCELFVQLWRGLGLELGYHWNFGMNPTICVLRFWNVDDHEGRQCLISHNG
CC   ASRITFNQSYPEINMDRVRTQFLQRMQTPELDEVVDEN
CC   ATRPA1HY4p is 215 aa long and is encoded by 5 exons (position
CC   9277-10327), it is similar to the ssDNA-binding portion of the
CC   large subunit of RPA1:
CC   MGLILADEHGMTIEATVGYKMSDHYKDFINEGEWVTITNFGVVENSGSVRATTHSFKIGF
CC   SVDTVVRLTSPVPAIPHYRLASFSSIIDDEIDKSVLVDLVGAIYDVGELINTRPKQNNVD
CC   DLTLTFKISDNENRVLECLATKKEALDFDHNYRRYGGGVIVAVLGWWKIDRYFDGPKNVR
CC   VCTAGPISTVFPDPDIPESNEIHEMLRDEGARNGG
CC   There is 95% nucleotide identity between ~4200-bp 5'-terminal
CC   portions of HELITRONY2 and HELITRON1; their ~360-bp 3'-termini
CC   are 87% identical with each other.

CC   HELITRONY3 is a nonautonomous HELITRON-like DNA transposon.
CC   There are ~10 copies of HELITRONY3 in the genome; they are ~95%
CC   identical to the consensus sequence.
CC   HELITRONY3 elements have been inserted precisely in the AT target
CC   sites,
CC   without duplication of the host DNA.

XX
CC   META1_I is an internal part of META1 LTR-retrotransposon;
CC   its LTR is deposited as META1_LTR. Presumably, META1
CC   has been transposed just a few million years ago.
CC   META1 proviruses and solo LTRs are bordered by 5 bp-long target
CC   site duplications.
CC   The consensus sequence has been reconstructed based on 9
CC   copies present in the GenBank 112.0 release.
CC   There is ~98% identity between the META1_I consensus sequence
CC   and META1_I copies.
CC   META1_I encodes only short protein similar to the 110-aa
CC   C-terminal
CC   portion of Copia-like polyproteins from plants and invertebrates.
CC   There is a very week similarity between this portion and RNASE H.
CC   The name has been changed from METAMORPH1_I to
CC   META1_I (Dec.16, 1999).
XX

DE   consensus.

RN   [2]
RP   1-1
RA   Kapitonov V.V. and Jurka J.;
RT   "SIMPLEGUY1.";
RL   Direct Submission to Repbase Update (31-OCT-1999).
XX
DR   [1] (Consensus)
XX
CC   SIMPLEGUY1 is a putative non-autonomous DNA transposon.
CC   Its individual copies are ~95% identical to the consensus
CC   sequence. They are bordered by 3 bp-long target site
CC   duplications.
CC   Putative target site is TAA.
CC   It has 15 bp-long perfect terminal inverted repeat.
CC   Internal portion of SIMPLEGUY1 includes 27 bp-long minisatellite;
CC   the number of the satellite monomers is a variable.
CC   Related minisatellite is present also in the Brasica genome
CC   (EST sequence AT000870).
CC   The minisatellite monomer codes 9 aa-long protein sequence
CC   similar to the FMRFamide-related neuropeptide.
XX

CC   SIMPLEHAT1 is a putative non-autonomous DNA transposon.
CC   Its individual copies are ~96% identical to the consensus and
CC   there are about 20-50 SIMPLEHAT1 copies scattered over the
CC   A.thaliana
CC   genome. They are bordered by 8 bp-long target site duplications
CC   and
CC   have 28 bp-long imperfect terminal inverted repeats.
CC   Internal portion of SIMPLEHAT1 includes 27 bp-long minisatellite;
CC   the number of the satellite monomers is a variable.
CC   Related minisatellite is present also in the Brasica genome
CC   (EST sequence AT000870) and in the SIMPLEGUY1 transposon.

XX
DR   [1] (Consensus)
XX
CC   SIMPLEHAT2 is a non-autonomous DNA transposon.
CC   Its individual copies are ~94% identical to the consensus and
CC   there are about 50 copies of SIMPLEHAT2 scattered in the
CC   A.thaliana
CC   genome. They are bordered by 8 bp-long target site duplications
CC   and
CC   have 19-bp terminal inverted repeats.
CC   Internal portion of SIMPLEHAT2 is composed of a 28-bp
CC   minisatellite repeat (21 copies of the minisatellite repeat are
CC   present
CC   in the consensus sequence). Related 27- and 28-bp minisatellites
CC   have been propagated also by the SIMPLEHAT1, SIMPLEGUY1 and
CC   ATREPX1
CC   transposons.  Updated by J. Jurka, Dec. 2005.
XX

RA   Kapitonov V.V. and Jurka J.;
RT   "TAG3N1, a non-autonomous DNA transposon.";
RL   Repbase Reports 1(3), 36-36 (2001).
XX
DR   [1] (Consensus)
XX
CC   TAG is a subfamily of HAT-like DNA transposons. TAG3N1 is 80%
CC   identical to the TAG1 autonomous transposon. There are ~10
CC   copies of TAG3N1 present in the genome, they are ~97% identical
CC   to the consensus sequence.
CC   TAG3N1 has imperfect 22-bp TIRs (4 mismatches) and is flanked by

XX
CC   VANDAL1 is an autonomous DNA transposon. It induces
CC   9-bp duplications of AT-rich target sites upon its integration
CC   in the genome. This DNA transposon does not have terminal
CC   inverted repeats. It encodes MUDRA-like transposase and
CC   one/two additional proteins in direct and reverse orientations,
CC   respectively. VANDAL1 copies are 96% identical to the consensus
CC   sequence. The most conservative transposase domain is encoded
CC   by the fragment which starts at position 2480 and ends at 2800.

CC   VANDAL13 is a molecular fossil of a VANDAL-like autonomous DNA
CC   transposon. It is bordered by a perfect 9 bp-long target site
CC   duplication. A VANDAL-like element closest to VANDAL13 is
CC   harbored
CC   by chromosome 3 (GenBank accession number AB024038, position
CC   73183 -> 60855); it is 92% identical to VANDAL13.
CC   VANDAL14 is the next transposon closest to VANDAL13, there is 72%
CC   nucleotide identity between these two elements. Two additional
CC   mobile elements, ATDNATA1 and ATSINE2A, are inserted in the only
CC   copy of VANDAL13; they were removed from the sequence reported
CC   here.
XX
SQ   Sequence 12147 BP; 3930 A; 2304 C; 2303 G; 3610 T; 0 other;

DR   [1] (Consensus)
XX
CC   VANDAL14 is an autonomous DNA transposon. It generates
CC   9 bp duplications of AT-rich target sites upon integration
CC   of its copies in the genome.
CC   There are 5 copies of VANDAL14, 100% identical to each other,
CC   we found in chromosomes I,III,IV and V. These copies are
CC   flanked by 9 bp duplications of different target sites.
CC   VANDAL14 encodes three putative proteins.

RL   Direct Submission to Repbase Update (MAR-2000).
XX
DR   [1] (Consensus)
XX
CC   VANDAL16 is a VANDAL-like DNA transposon. It generates
CC   9 bp duplications of AT-rich target sites upon integration
CC   of its copies in the genome.
CC   There are 2 copies of VANDAL16, 100% identical to each other,
CC   we found in chromosomes I and III. These copies are
CC   flanked by 9 bp duplications of different target sites, and
CC   they carry ATGP9LTR, a long terminal repeat from the ATGP9
CC   Gypsy-like retrovirus (position 4624-5131) flanked by 5 bp
CC   duplication of a target site CAAGC. Putative ancestor of
CC   VANDAL16 is a VANDAL15-like transposon free of the ATGP9LTR
CC   insertion.
XX

CC   VANDAL18 is a fossil of an autonomous DNA transposon.
CC   It is flanked by a 9 bp target site duplication.
CC   Its non-autonomous derivate is NVANDAL18A.
CC   It preserves short subterminal inverted repeats.
CC   It encodes MUDR like transposase (~position 400-3600), which
CC   is most similar to the transposase encoded by VANDAL2 and VANDAL1
CC   transposons.
CC   Another protein is encoded by the second strand, position
CC   10975-6714. It is similar to the proteins encoded by
CC   other VANDAL-like transposon, including the SUMO-like proteases.
CC   This protein is encoded by 15 exons, predicted by GENSCAN:.
XX

XX
DR   [1] (Consensus)
XX
CC   VANDAL18NA is a consensus sequence of a non-autonomous DNA
CC   transposon. Its copies are flanked by 9 bp duplications of
CC   different target sites, and they are ~92% identical to the
CC   consensus sequence. There are ~10 copies of VANDAL18NA in
CC   the genome. VANDAL18 is an autonomous transposon that was
CC   involved in transposition of VANDAL18NA.
CC   VANDAL18NA has 97-bp terminal inverted repeat; copies of the
CC   repeat are 73% identical to each other.
CC   VANDAL18NA carries a second inverted repeat at positions 443-636
CC   and 803-995, copies of the repeat are 82% identical to each
CC   other.
XX

DR   [1] (Consensus)
XX
CC   VANDAL2 is an autonomous DNA transposon. It induces
CC   9-bp duplications of AT-rich target sites upon its integration
CC   in the genome. This DNA transposon does not have terminal
CC   inverted repeats. It encodes MUDRA-like transposase and
CC   one/two additional proteins in direct and reverse orientations,
CC   respectively. VANDAL2 copies are ~98% identical to the VANDAL2
CC   consensus sequence. VANDAL1 and VANDAL2 consensus sequence
CC   are 65% identical to each other. The most conservative
CC   transposase
CC   domain is encoded by a region which starts at position 2385 and
CC   ends at position 3025.
XX

RN   [1]
RP   1-12720
RA   Kapitonov V.V. and Jurka J.;
RT   "VANDAL20, a family of monstrous MuDR-like DNA transposons.";
RL   Repbase Reports 1(4), 31-31 (2001).
XX
DR   GenBank; AL161499; Positions  104443   91724.
XX
CC   VANDAL20 is a fossil of a MuDR-like autonomous DNA transposon.
CC   It has been active transpositionally relatively recently;
CC   its exon/intron structure is well preserved, and it is flanked
CC   by a perfect 9-bp target site duplication (TTAATTAAG).
CC   VANDAL20 has imperfect subterminal 52-bp inverted repeats (8
CC   mismatches, positions 17-68 and 12704-12653).
CC   A 8790aa MuDR-like transposase, VANDAL20p1, is encoded by 4
CC   exons (predicted by FGENESH and GENSCAN).
CC   CDS join(610..616,709..2656,2811..3405,3479..3568)
CC   A ~224-aa protein of unknown function is encoded by one or
CC   two exons in a region 4794-5464. X masks a short deletion
CC   reconstructed based on sequences of VANDAL20p2-like proteins
CC   encoded by different VANDALs.
CC   VANDAL20p2 is 25% identical (blastp, E=3e-11) to VANDAL20p3,
CC   a 201-aa protein encoded by the second strand.
CC   CDS	complement(join(6864..7457,7570..7581))
CC   VANDAL20's second strand encoded also a 958-aa protein called
CC   VANDAL20p4.
CC   CDS	complement(join(8459..9082,9169..9252,9331..9585,
CC   9664..9831,10128..10388,10477..10959,11102..11461,
CC   11629..12033,12144..12269,12368..12466))
CC   C-terminal portion of VANDAL20p4 is similar to the SUMO-like
CC   protease, which is present in highly divergent forms in
CC   different VANDAL-like families. These proteases are functional
CC   elements of VANDALs that help them to multiply.
XX

CC   VANDAL21 is a consensus sequence of a VANDAL-like autonomous DNA
CC   transposon. It was reconstructed based on six copies of the
CC   transposon. These copies are flanked by 9 bp duplications of
CC   different
CC   target sites, and they are ~98% identical to the consensus
CC   sequence.
CC   VANDAL21 encodes three proteins, VANDAL21p1, VANDAL21p2 and
CC   VANDAL21p3. VANDAL21p1 is a 778-aa MuDrA-like transposase.
CC   Functions of 132-aa VANDAL21p2 and 718-aa VANDAL21p3 are
CC   unknown.
XX

XX
CC   VANDAL22 is a fossil of a MuDR-like autonomous DNA transposon.
CC   It has been active transpositionally relatively recently since
CC   it is inserted in the ATREP10D copy and is flanked by a perfect
CC   9-bp target site duplication. MuDR transposase is also well
CC   preserved (positions 490-3398). VANDAL22 encodes also two
CC   proteins by the second strand (positions 5190-4547 and
CC   9626-6458).

CC   VANDAL2N1 is an nonautonomous DNA transposon. It has generated
CC   9-bp target site duplications upon its integration
CC   in the genome. VANDAL2N1 has encoded a portion of a MuDr-like
CC   transposase.
CC   There are 5 copies of VANDAL2N1 in the genome, they are ~98%
CC   identical to the consensus sequence.
CC   VANDAL2N1 is 85% identical to VANDAL2.

RL   Direct Submission to Repbase Update (JAN-2000).
XX
DR   [1] (Consensus)
XX
CC   VANDAL3 is a putative autonomous DNA transposon. It generates
CC   9-bp duplications of AT-rich target sites upon its integration
CC   in the genome.
CC   There are ~10 copies of VANDAL3 in the genome, they are ~98%
CC   identical to the consensus sequence.
CC   VANDAL3 encodes a transposase (putative exons at 1014-2153,
CC   2379-3251,
CC   and 3448-3846) ~32% identical to the mudrA transposase from the
CC   maize transposon MuDR. VANDAL3 encodes also two additional
CC   proteins in a reverse orientation. One of them (position
CC   5425-4411)
CC   is similar to the RPA70 subunit of the replication protein A
CC   in eukaryotes and atchaea. The protein is preserved in several
CC   families
CC   of VANDAL-like transposons which show as low as 60-70% nucleotide
CC   identity to each other. Therefore, this protein may be involved
CC   in
CC   a transposition of 10-20 kb-long VANDALs and ARNOLD-like
CC   elements.
CC   The second protein (position 15619-11548) has low similarity to
CC   different structural proteins.
XX

CC   VANDAL6 is a putative autonomous DNA transposon. It generates
CC   9-bp duplications of AT-rich target sites upon its integration

CC   VANDAL7 is a putative autonomous DNA transposon. It generates
CC   9-bp duplications of AT-rich target sites upon its integration
CC   in the genome.
CC   There are ~10 copies of VANDAL7 in the genome, they are ~98%
CC   identical to the consensus sequence.

CC   VANDAL8 is a putative autonomous DNA transposon. It generates
CC   9-bp duplications of AT-rich target sites upon its integration
CC   in the genome.
CC   There are ~10 copies of VANDAL8 in the genome, they are ~98%
CC   identical to the consensus sequence.

XX
OS   Arabidopsis thaliana
OC   Eukaryota; Viridiplantae; Streptophyta; Embryophyta; Tracheophyta;
OC   Spermatophyta; Magnoliophyta; eudicotyledons; Gunneridae;
OC   Pentapetalae; rosids; malvids; Brassicales; Brassicaceae;

RA   Kapitonov V.V. and Jurka J.;
RT   "VANDAL9.";
RL   Direct Submission to Repbase Update (MAR-2000).
XX
DR   [1] (Consensus)
XX
CC   VANDAL9 is an autonomous DNA transposon. It generates
CC   9 bp duplications of AT-rich target sites upon integration
CC   of its copies in the genome.
CC   There are 2 copies of VANDAL9, 95% identical to each other,
CC   we found in chromosomes I and II (AC005561 53629<-42112 and
CC   AC021198 44375->56770). These copies are flanked by 9 bp
CC   duplications
CC   of different target sites, AATAATTTA and TATAARTTA, respectively.
CC   VANDAL9 encode two proteins.

RL   Direct Submission to Repbase Update (SEP-2000).
XX
DR   [1] (Consensus)
XX
CC   VANDALNX1 is a nonautonomous DNA transposon. Its copies are
CC   flanked by 9 bp target site duplications.
CC   There are 3 copies of VANDALNX1 in the genome, they are ~97%
CC   identical to the consensus sequence.
CC   Both ~80-bp 5'- and 3'-termini of VANDALNX1 are 70-75% identical
CC   to the corresponding termini of VANDAL10, VANDAL11 and VANDAL12.
CC   Therefore, it's likely that the unknown autonomous element, which
CC   was directly involved in transposition of VANDALNX1 copies, was
CC   similar to VANDAL10-VANDAL12 transposons.
XX
SQ   Sequence 1728 BP; 684 A; 272 C; 316 G; 456 T; 0 other;
